-2,8,15,10,10,7,14,10,10,14,15,-4,7,-23,-28,-53,-7,-38,-7,-10,-13,-12,-14,-14,
-10,-35,-35,-17,-41,-5,0,0,-1,-20,-10,-30,34,34,39,41,27,-27,0,0,-28,-24,-15,
-23,0,-32,-59,-70,-70,-89,-72,-81,-8,-28,0,0,66,63,63,41,36]} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5
Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Bd2 e6 7. Bc4 Bb4 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3
Qb6 10. O-O $6 {After this move, Black has good and easy play. More critical
is 10.d5} Nc6 $1 11. Ne5 $6 {Hardly ever a good idea in the Neo-Scandinavian} (
11. d5 $2 O-O-O $17) 11... Ne4 $1 $15 (11... O-O $15 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Bb3 Be4
$3 14. f3 Bd5 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Qd3 (16. Bd2 Qb6 $17) 16... Nxc3 $1 17. Qxc3
Qxc3 $15) 12. Nxc6 Nxc3 $1 13. bxc3 {Now that White's structure is broken,
Black is clearly better} Qxc6 $15 14. Bd3 Bxd3 $1 (14... Bg6 {allows White to
double up Black's pawns for no real reason} 15. c4 O-O 16. Bxg6 hxg6) 15. Qxd3
O-O $15 16. Rfe1 Rfd8 17. Rab1 b6 18. Re3 Qd6 $17 (18... Rd6 $1 $17 19. h3 Rad8
) 19. a4 Rd7 20. a5 g6 (20... Qa3 $1 $15 21. Re5 Qa2) 21. g3 Rad8 22. Qa6 Qa3
23. Qxa7 bxa5 24. Rb5 c6 25. Rb7 Rxb7 26. Qxb7 Qc1+ 27. Kg2 a4 28. Rf3 Rf8 29.
Qxc6 Qxc2 30. c4 Kg7 31. h4 Qb2 32. Qa6 Qxd4 33. Qxa4 Rc8 34. Rf4 Qc5 35. Qd7
Rf8 36. h5 Qxh5 37. Qe7 Qa5 38. c5 Qa8+ 39. Kh2 Qe8 40. Qc7 e5 41. Re4 Qc8 42.
Qxe5+ Kg8 43. Re3 Qc6 1/2-1/2

