{[%evp 0,162,17,28,45,41,64,64,64,62,96,96,97,62,78,30,24,40,77,54,32,27,16,18,
23,9,10,10,13,10,4,-15,2,5,7,4,3,5,3,-8,-4,-15,1,11,-9,0,-15,-12,-14,-36,1,-57,
-53,-62,-27,-26,-36,-32,-25,-72,-58,-60,-43,-56,-50,-55,-52,-53,-62,-81,-66,
-80,-88,-84,-84,-81,-77,-77,-104,-107,-106,-154,-151,-156,-94,-119,-128,-172,
-181,-188,-189,-228,-227,-226,-226,-226,-226,-227,-226,-226,-225,-225,-225,
-225,-225,-225,-225,-222,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,
-202,-202,-202,-207,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-220,-225,
-226,-249,-267,-274,-275,-275,-289,-243,-248,-278,-280,-213,-212,-175,-232,
-193,-238,-244,-244,-262,-244,-244,-485,-485,-507,-485,-485,-495,-497,-505,
-505,-507]} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {It is important to note that if White
manages to advance his c pawn early on, he would have an edge. Fortunately for
Black, this is rarely feasible as Nc3 blocks the pawn. Therefore, even though
Black has wasted a couple of tempi going back in forth with the queen, White
is not able to directly exploit it} 3. Nc3 (3. Ke2 Qe4# {A funny little line
that serves as an example that White should play carefully :)}) (3. c4 Qe4+ {
is not what White hoped for}) 3... Qa5 {We are mostly going to focus on the
Qa5 Scandinavian as I find it the most principled variation} 4. d4 ({A sample
line that shows how the game might go if White does not fight for an opening
advantage} 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Be2 c6 6. O-O Bf5 7. d4 e6 8. Be3 Nbd7 9. a3 (9. h3
Bb4) 9... Bd6 10. h3 O-O (10... h6)) 4... c6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8.
O-O {A lot of the time people decide to play quietly in the Scandinavian in
order to avoid theory. In such cases, Black is doing more than fine and gets a
healthy active position similar to the one in the game} Bd6 (8... Bb4 $5 {
is an interesting possibility too}) 9. Bf4 Qc7 10. Qe2 {White tries to simply
put his pieces in the center and go from there. However, this is not precise
enough and Black can take advantage of such an unambitious approach} O-O 11.
Rad1 Nd5 $1 {A typical idea looking to put some pressure on the opponent. Much
better than the simplistic 11...Nbd7} (11... Nbd7 {also leads to equality for
Black} 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Yd6b4] The exchanges
served Black's interests: he is now ready to start putting pressure on the d4
pawn and poke White's weaknesses on the queenside with Qb4. It is in his favor
to go into a heavy piece endgame} 14. f3 (14. Bd3 Rad8 $15 ({A sample variation
} 14... Bxd3 {Such position often arises and although it seems equal, Black is
the one with the initiative} 15. Qxd3 Rad8 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 {[%csl Yd4]
Only Black can press for a win} Qb4 (17... Qd5 {is another key idea} 18. Qxd5
cxd5 {The typical capture: Black intends to double his rooks along the c file
and then start a minority attack with the a and b pawns} 19. Rfe1 Rc8 20. c3
Rc4 $15) (17... h6 {illustrates another way to play the position} 18. c3 Rd7 (
18... Qd5 $5 19. Qb1 {is what I believe White's response should be}) 19. h3
Rfd8 {[%cal Yc6c5,Ye6e5] Black threatens to exploit the pin of the d4 pawn at
any time with e5 or c5} 20. Qc2 Qf4 21. Rfe1 Rd5 22. Re4 Qc7 23. c4 R5d6 {
White is forced to defend which is not easy} 24. Qe2 Qa5 25. a3 b5 {A common
idea to get better control of the center} 26. c5 Rd5 {Black has a risk-free
game and can press for a long time}))) 14... Rad8 15. Bb3) 12. Bg3 (12. Nxd5
cxd5 $1 {Capturing this way indicates that Black is planning a minority attack
on the queenside} 13. Bd3 Bxd3 (13... f6 {The most direct choice where the
complications are in Black's favor} 14. Bxf5 exf5 15. Ng6 hxg6 16. Qe6+ Qf7 17.
Qxf7+ Kxf7 18. Bxd6 Re8 19. Bxb8 (19. Rfe1 $4 Nc6 $17) 19... Raxb8 20. Rfe1 g5
$15) 14. Rxd3 Nc6 15. Bg3 {for illustrative purposes} Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17.
dxe5 Rac8 $15 18. c3 Qc4 {Black has a great outpost on c4} ({or} 18... Qa5 19.
a3 Rc4)) (12. Bxd5 exd5 $15 {Black has the bishop pair and a great position!} (
12... cxd5 {is the strategically better choice but it does not work tactically
here} 13. Nb5 ({If the position looked like this, it would be the dream:} 13.
Bg3 a6 14. Rfe1 Nc6 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 {[%cal Yf8c8,Yc8c4,Ya8c8,Yb7b5]
The pawns on c2 and b2 are weak})) 13. Bg3 Nd7 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16.
a3 (16. Rfe1 Qb4) 16... Rfe8 17. Qd2 Qg6 18. Rc1 h5 (18... Re6)) 12... Nxc3 $1
{Black has managed to destroy White's structure. Although objectively the
position is still equal, White cannot afford to make a mistake now as his
weaknesses will begin to tell.} 13. bxc3 Nd7 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Bb3 (15. Bxd6
Qxd6 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. cxd3 {shows poor positional understanding: White made
all the exchanges that favor his opponent} c5 {White's pawn structure is
vulnerable to pawn breaks by Black} (17... b5) 18. dxc5 Qxc5 19. Qb2 b6 20.
Rfe1 Rac8 21. Rc1 Rfd8) 15... Bg6 $5 (15... Bxg3 16. hxg3 {does not promise
Black anything since White will push the g pawn very fast}) 16. c4 $6 (16. Bxd6
Qxd6) 16... Bxg3 $1 17. hxg3 c5 $1 {[%csl Ya2,Rb3,Yc2,Yc4] Blocking the c4 pawn
} 18. c3 (18. d5 Rae8 $1 19. dxe6 (19. d6 e5 20. Rd5 e4) (19. c3) (19. Rfe1 e5
20. c3 Qd6 21. Bc2 e4 22. Rb1 Re7) 19... Qxe6 20. Qxe6 Rxe6 21. Rd7 Be4 $15)
18... Rac8 19. Rd2 h6 20. Rfd1 Qd6 $5 {A nice positional trap... that worked!}
21. Qe5 Rfd8 $1 22. Qxd6 Rxd6 23. dxc5 Rxd2 24. Rxd2 Be4 $3 {The key move
behind all the operations after 20...Qd6. The endgame is better for Black
because of his superior structure and better minor piece} (24... Rxc5 $2 25.
Rd8+ Kh7 26. Rd7 $16) 25. Ba4 (25. f3 Bc6 $15) 25... Rxc5 26. f3 Bg6 $1 27. Bb3
(27. Rd7 Rxc4 28. Bb3 Rxc3 29. Rxb7 a6 $17) (27. Rd8+ Kh7 28. Rd7 Rxc4 29. Bb3
Rxc3 30. Rxb7 a5 (30... a6 31. Rb6 Bd3)) 27... Rc7 $1 28. Rd8+ Kh7 29. Kf2 $2 {
A positional mistake that allows Black to fixate his opponent's structure on
the kingside. The correct move was 29.g4 with chances to hold} h5 $3 {[#] Now,
White can never touch any of his g2-g3-f3 pawns: any pawn move only creates
additional weaknesses!} 30. Ke3 e5 $1 $17 {the idea is f6-Bf7-g6-Kg7} 31. f4 $6
{A desperate attempt for counterplay that only creates more weaknesses!} (31.
Ke2 f6 32. Kd2 Bf7 33. Kd3 g6 34. Ra8 b6 35. Rd8 Kg7 36. Rb8 Be6) 31... Re7 $1
32. Kf2 Be4 $1 {Xg2....Xb7!} (32... e4 $4 33. Ke3) 33. c5 Kg6 34. Bd5 Bxd5 35.
Rxd5 f6 $1 36. Kf3 $1 (36. fxe5 Rxe5 37. Rd7 Rf5+ $3 {Xg3} 38. Kg1 Rxc5 39.
Rxb7 Rxc3 40. Kh2 (40. Rxa7 Rxg3 41. Kf2 Rc3 42. a4 h4 43. a5 h3 44. gxh3 Rxh3
45. a6 Ra3 46. Ra8 Kf5 47. a7 Kf4 (47... g5 48. Kg2 Kf4 (48... g4 49. Kf2 Kf4
50. Rf8 Ra2+ 51. Kf1 (51. Kg1 Rxa7 52. Rxf6+ Kg3 53. Rf1) 51... Rxa7 52. Rxf6+
Kg3 53. Rg6 Ra1+ 54. Ke2 Kh3 55. Kf2 Ra2+ 56. Kg1 Kg3 57. Kf1 Ra1+ 58. Ke2 Rg1
59. Rg8 Kh2 60. Rg7 g3 61. Rg8 Kg2 62. Rg7 Ra1 63. Rg8 Ra7 64. Rg6 Re7+ 65. Kd2
Kf2 66. Rf6+ Kg1 67. Rg6 g2)) 48. Kg2 f5 49. Kf2 Ra2+ 50. Kf1 Kg4 51. Kg1 f4
52. Kf1 Kf3) 40... Ra3 $19) 36... Kf5 37. a4 g6 $1 38. c4 Rc7 39. fxe5 fxe5 40.
g4+ $5 hxg4+ 41. Ke3 b6 $3 {As a reminder precise calculation is what matters
most in chess!} 42. cxb6 axb6 43. Kd3 Ra7 44. Rd6 Rxa4 45. Rxb6 Ra3+ $1 46. Ke2
Ra2+ 47. Kf1 Rc2 $2 {The correct move is 47... g3 -/+ putting the White king
in a cage} 48. g3 $3 (48. Rc6 $2 g3 $19) 48... Rxc4 49. Rb2 Rc3 50. Kg2 Ke4 51.
Rb4+ Kf5 52. Rb2 Rd3 53. Kf2 Rc3 54. Ra2 Rb3 55. Kg2 Ke4 56. Ra4+ Kf5 57. Ra2
Rb5 58. Kf2 Rd5 59. Ke3 Rd1 $3 {now Rf1 is the lethal threat!} 60. Rf2+ Ke6 61.
Rf8 Re1+ $3 62. Kf2 Rb1 63. Ra8 Rb2+ 64. Ke3 Rg2 65. Ke4 Kf6 $3 66. Ra6+ Kg5
67. Ra3 Re2+ $1 68. Kd3 Rf2 $1 69. Ke4 Rf3 70. Ra5 Rxg3 71. Rxe5+ Kh4 72. Re6
Rf3 (72... g5 $5 73. Rh6#) 73. Rxg6 Rf8 74. Ke3 Kh3 75. Ke2 g3 76. Rh6+ Kg2 77.
Rh7 Re8+ 78. Kd2 Kf2 79. Rf7+ Kg1 80. Rg7 g2 81. Rh7 Re5 0-1

