{[%evp 0,110,19,38,60,60,55,48,20,38,48,49,49,55,42,26,61,38,53,41,39,38,44,48,
46,48,48,31,30,28,27,-8,8,7,0,-3,-8,-2,0,-3,-27,-36,-49,-52,-48,-61,-61,-52,
-47,-82,-83,-105,-98,-93,-76,-96,-50,-49,-49,-46,-44,-81,-81,-81,-81,-54,-54,
-54,-54,-54,-64,-63,-63,-69,-93,-107,-103,-100,-89,-94,-90,-94,-94,-125,-125,
-128,-111,-128,-131,-109,-131,-149,-126,-129,-130,-167,-171,-157,-126,-135,
-133,-140,-148,-214,-243,-336,-319,-346,-365,-507,-506,-519,-527] A great
example of typical play in the Scandinavian/ Caro-Kann structure. Black
promptly achieved his plan of getting a heavy piece endgame where only he can
be better} 1. e4 c6 (1... d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6.
Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 {The game has a similar structure to this one} 8. O-O Be7 (
8... c6) 9. Ne4 Nbd7 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 11. c3 O-O 12. Bf4 c6 $11) 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2
dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. c3 Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 9. Be2 e6 10.
O-O Be7 (10... Bd6 {The bishop is not properly placed there: Black does not
have an attack on the kingside and only allows an unpleasant pin after White
plays Bg5} 11. Ne5 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 O-O 13. Bg5) 11. Ne5 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 O-O 13. Bg5
h6 {a useful prophylaxis} 14. Bxf6 (14. Bh4 $5 Nd7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Nxd7 Qxd7
{is very pleasant for Black because he is the one dictating the course of the
game} 17. Rad1 Rad8 18. Rd3 (18. Qd3 Qc7 $15) 18... Qc7 19. Rfd1 Rd6 20. a3
Rfd8 21. R3d2 Qd7 22. b4 b6 23. Qe3 Rd5 24. c4 Rd6 25. Qe4 b5 $15) 14... Bxf6
15. b4 {White has a positional break and Black needs to react accordingly} (15.
Rad1 Qd5 {A provocative move} 16. c4 Qd6 17. Rd3 c5 $11 (17... Rad8)) 15... a5
$1 (15... Rb8 16. Nc4 $11) (15... Rc8 {is bad because it lets White keep the
knight on the board. White is able to apply some pressure on the queenside
after} 16. Nc4 Qc7 17. Rad1 b6 18. Rd3 c5 19. dxc5 bxc5 20. b5 $16 {[%cal
Ya2a4,Ya4a5,Yb5b6] Black's position is miserable}) 16. a3 Bxe5 $1 17. dxe5 (17.
Qxe5 Qd5 $11 {[%cal Yd5b3,Yc6d5]}) 17... Qc7 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 $15 {intending Rd5}
19. f4 (19. g3 {is a random move which allows me to demonstrate Black's plan:}
Rd5 20. f4 (20. Rxd5 cxd5) 20... Rad8 21. Rxd5 cxd5 $19) 19... Rd5 20. Kh1 Rad8
21. Rac1 Qd7 22. Rxd5 Qxd5 23. c4 Qd3 24. Qe1 axb4 25. Qxb4 Qe3 26. Rf1 Qe2 27.
Rg1 Rd7 28. c5 Qf2 29. a4 g6 30. a5 Kg7 (30... Qd4 31. Rb1 Qxb4 32. Rxb4 Rd1+
33. Kh2 Ra1 34. Rxb7 Rxa5 35. h4 Rxc5 36. Rc7 g5 37. fxg5 hxg5 38. hxg5 Rxe5
39. Rxc6 Rxg5 40. g3 Ra5 41. Kg2 Kg7 42. Kf3 Ra3+ 43. Kf2 e5 44. Rb6 (44. Rc8)
44... f6 45. Rc6 Kg6 46. Rb6 Kg5 47. Rc6 e4 48. Rb6 f5 49. Rc6 (49. Rb8 Ra2+
50. Ke3 Rg2 51. Rg8+ Kf6) 49... Ra2+ 50. Kf1 Kg4 51. Rc3 $19) 31. Kh2 h5 32.
Kh1 h4 (32... Qd4 33. Rb1 Qxb4 (33... Qf2 $17) 34. Rxb4 Rd1+ 35. Kh2 Ra1 36.
Rxb7 Rxa5 37. h4 Rxc5 38. Kg3 Rc3+ 39. Kf2 c5 40. Rb8 $15) 33. Kh2 Qe3 34. Kh1
Qd4 35. Rb1 Qxb4 36. Rxb4 Rd1+ 37. Kh2 Ra1 38. Rxb7 Rxa5 39. Kg1 Rxc5 40. Kf2
g5 41. Rb4 Rc2+ 42. Kf3 Rc3+ 43. Kf2 c5 44. Ra4 Kg6 45. fxg5 Kxg5 46. Ra7 Kg6
47. Rc7 c4 48. Ke2 Rc2+ 49. Kf3 c3 50. Rc4 Kf5 51. Rf4+ Kxe5 52. Rxf7 Rd2 53.
Rc7 c2 54. g3 hxg3 55. Kxg3 Kd4 0-1

