{[%evp 0,74,28,18,45,44,64,64,64,53,49,47,77,68,62,62,54,55,48,69,63,72,76,64,
72,57,66,-4,25,-32,-81,-81,-27,-33,-62,-56,-57,-65,2,-16,-25,-15,9,-22,-43,-33,
0,0,0,-28,-18,-22,4,-68,-68,-61,-57,-315,-115,-1245,-1543,-1543,-263,-29995,
-29992,-29993,-29994,-29995,-29996,-29997,-29990,-29995,-29996,-29997,-29990,
-29991,-29992] A sample game on how to navigate the structure after taking on
e5. White created a lot of weaknesses which he later was unable to defend} 1.
e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 $2 {is an
unnecessary concession} 7. Qxf3 c6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. d4 e6 10. Bf4 Be7 11. Rfe1
O-O 12. Rad1 Rfe8 13. Be5 $2 (13. Ne4 {keeps White's chances slightly more
preferable}) 13... Rad8 14. Ne4 (14. Bf4 $11 {is surprisingly White's best
move: he should acknowledge his mistake and keep the bishop on board}) (14.
Bxf6 Nxf6 $11) 14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Rxd1 17. Rxd1 Rd8 18. Rxd8+
Qxd8 (18... Bxd8 $1 $17 {White has a passive bishop and a lot of potential
weaknesses. Black's plan is to provoke f4 and then exploit the dark squares
around the white king} 19. g3 g6 20. c3 Bc7 $3 21. f4 Bb6+ {[%cal Ya5c5]}) 19.
Bd3 g6 20. c3 Bc5 21. b4 Bb6 22. c4 c5 $1 {creating an outpost for the bishop
on d4} 23. b5 Ba5 $3 {Black maneuvers the bishop and targets his opponent's
king} 24. Kh2 Bc3 25. f4 Qd7 26. Be2 Qd2 27. a4 Bd4 28. Bf3 Qc1 29. Qxb7 Qg1+ (
29... Bg1+ 30. Kg3 $19) 30. Kg3 h5 31. f5 Bxe5+ 32. Kh4 Qf2+ 33. Kg5 Qg3+ 34.
Bg4 hxg4 35. fxg6 gxh3+ 36. Kh5 Qxg6+ 37. Kh4 hxg2 0-1

