-348,-353,-364,-312]} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 c6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6.
Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 (8... Bd6 {is my game with GM Hatanbaatar}) 9.
Bf4 {White plays natural moves without caring too much about precision:
something Black should always welcome in the Scandinavian} (9. Nxd7 Kxd7 {
is a curious idea although I would not recommend it. In my opinion, it
complicates things unnecessarily} 10. Be3 Rd8 $11) 9... Bb4 $5 {fast
development} 10. Nxd7 (10. Ne2 O-O 11. c3 Be7 {Black's position is very solid})
10... Nxd7 11. Ne2 O-O 12. Ng3 Bg6 {Black has a stable position with active
pieces and no weaknesses} 13. c3 Be7 {[%csl Yg3] White's knight is heavily
restricted and, in fact, it would be much better placed on f3} 14. Qe2 (14. Bd3
Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Nf6 {A typical position. Obejectively, it is equal but there is
still everything to play for!} 16. Ne4 Rfd8 17. Be5 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Bd6 19. Rfd1
Bxe5 20. Qxe5 (20. dxe5 Qxa2) 20... Rd5 21. Qe2 Rad8 22. g3 h6 {back rank
prophylaxis} 23. Rd2 R8d7 24. a3 Qd8 25. Rc2 {[%cal Yc6c5]} c5 26. dxc5 Rxc5 {
Black's chances are preferable becase he controls the only open file}) 14...
Nf6 15. Rfe1 {White is playing without a plan} (15. Qe5 Qxe5 16. dxe5 Nd7 $15 {
[%csl Rg3]} (16... Nd5 $15 17. Bxd5 cxd5) 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 {[%cal Yd7c5]} 18. Kf1
{Black has a wide choice of good moves} a5 (18... b5 $17) (18... Nc5 $17) 19.
a4 Nc5 $17 (19... h5 $17)) 15... Nd5 $1 16. Bd2 (16. Bxd5 $2 cxd5 (16... Qxd5
$5 $15)) 16... Qb6 $3 {[%cal Yb6b2] Preventing White's intended consolidation 
(Rad1 and Bc1)} (16... Rad8 {is imprecise since it allows White to re-group}
17. Rad1 Qb6 (17... Bf6 18. Bc1) 18. Bc1 $1 $11) (16... b5 17. Bb3 $11) 17. Be3
(17. Bb3 a5 18. c4 a4 (18... Nb4)) (17. Rad1 Rfd8 18. Bc1) 17... Nxe3 18. fxe3
$1 Bh4 $17 {Going for a simplified position where White's structure would be
destroyed} (18... Rad8 $17 19. Rad1 Qc7 (19... c5)) 19. b4 a5 20. a3 Bxg3 21.
hxg3 Qc7 22. Qf3 e5 23. g4 Rfe8 (23... h6 $1 {is better: it stops the further
advances of the g pawn leaving it vulnerable on a light square forever}) 24. g3
h6 25. Rf1 Ra7 $3 {Preparing to open the a file} 26. d5 (26. Rad1 axb4 27. axb4
Ra3 $19) 26... b5 27. d6 Qxd6 28. Rad1 Qc7 29. Be2 axb4 30. axb4 Ra3 31. c4
bxc4 32. Bxc4 Rf8 33. Rde1 Qb6 34. Be6 Qxb4 35. Bf5 Bxf5 36. Qxf5 Ra2 37. Rb1
Qd2 38. Qf2 Qxf2+ 39. Rxf2 Rxf2 40. Kxf2 c5 41. Rc1 Rc8 42. Rc4 f6 43. Kf3 Kf7
44. Ke4 Kg6 45. Kd5 Kg5 46. Ke6 Rc7 47. Kd6 Ra7 0-1

