-56,-68,-86,-93,-90,-97,-97,-78,-83,-88,-89,-93,-91,-92,-101,-100,-100,-100,
-93,-100,-93,-100,-93,-93,-104,-112,-124,-120,-126,-121,-121,-117,-126,-147,
-147,-149,-165,-162,-162,-153,-149,-165,-165,-146,-166,-168,-188,-174,-209,
-208,-231,-236] A battle where White had the bishop pair but a compromised
structure. Practically, it is very difficult to keep the balance from White's
side as Black's play is way more natural and easy. As Black, we shall keep in
mind the idea of b7-b5} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. d4 c6 6.
Bd3 Bg4 7. Ne4 Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Nd7 9. c3 Nf6 10. Bc2 Qd5 $11 {There is no
stopping Black from inflicting damage on his opponent's structure after taking
twice on f3} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Qxf3 13. gxf3 {[%csl Yf2,Yf3,Rf4,Yh3]} e6 14.
Bg5 Nd5 15. Be4 Bd6 {[%csl Rf4]} 16. Ke2 (16. Bxd5 {is a positional mistake.
Either recapture with a pawn is in Black's favor} exd5 $17 {[%cal Ye8d7,Yd7e6,
Ye6f5]} (16... cxd5 $15 {[%cal Ya8c8,Yc8c4,Yb7b5,Ya7a5,Yb5b4]})) 16... Kd7 17.
Be3 g6 18. Rad1 b5 $1 {[%csl Yc4] stopping c4} 19. Rc1 a5 $1 {[%cal Ya5a4]} 20.
c4 bxc4 21. Rxc4 {The weakness on c6 is compensated by the weakness on b2. In
case of b3, Black will continue with a4} Rhb8 22. Rb1 (22. b3 a4 $19 {[%cal
Ya8a2,Yb8b2]}) 22... Rb4 23. Rxb4 axb4 24. Ra1 Nxe3 (24... Ra5 $17 25. Bd2 f5
26. Bd3 e5 $17) 25. fxe3 Ra5 26. f4 c5 27. dxc5 Bxc5 28. a3 bxa3 29. bxa3 Bxa3
30. Kf3 Ke7 31. Bd3 Kf6 32. Ra2 e5 33. Bc4 exf4 34. exf4 Rc5 35. Rc2 Rc7 36.
Bb3 Rd7 37. Rc3 Bb4 38. Rc6+ Kg7 39. Bc4 f5 40. Be2 Ra7 41. Ba6 Kh6 42. Rb6 Bc5
43. Rc6 Bg1 44. Kg2 Bd4 45. Kg3 Re7 46. Rc4 Re3+ 47. Kg2 Bf6 48. Bb7 Bh4 49.
Bf3 Rb3 50. Bd1 Rg3+ 51. Kh2 Rd3 52. Ba4 Rd2+ 53. Kg1 Bg3 54. Bc6 Kh5 55. Bg2
Kh4 56. Ra4 Bf2+ 57. Kh2 Be3 0-1

