{[%evp 0,102,28,32,67,67,67,38,71,68,41,48,38,43,4,6,23,-13,2,4,8,11,36,37,40,
16,47,25,25,6,12,7,6,11,17,10,10,17,10,9,19,18,16,-11,-16,-18,-23,-34,-33,-33,
-33,-36,-55,-59,-59,-55,-55,-54,-45,-54,-54,-54,-54,-46,-46,-46,-46,-46,-60,
-106,-106,-106,-113,-106,-149,-129,-126,-105,-105,-183,-178,-212,-247,-254,
-282,-273,-276,-276,-285,-294,-294,-294,-294,-292,-292,-304,-329,-342,-376,
-417,-422,-2202,-1830,-2326,-29980] A great example of a minority attack in
the endgame by Karpov} 1. e4 c6 (1... d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Nf3 Bg4 5.
d4 e6 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Bd3 (8. Bd2) 8... Nf6 9. O-O {Black has given
up the bishop pair and as a result, he is slightly worse} Nbd7 10. Ne4 Be7 11.
Nxf6+ Nxf6 12. c3 O-O 13. Re1 (13. Bf4 Qd5 14. Qe2 $14 {To keep the slight
advantage, White needs to preserve the queens and his bishops on the board}) (
13. Bg5 {is of course not possible. The line is just an example of how Black
should treat the position if a case of opposite-colored bishops arises} Rfd8
14. Bxf6 Bxf6 {It is easier to play as Black because there are some ideas
which can pose practical problems for his opponent} 15. Qe4 g6 16. Rfd1 Qc7 17.
Qe2 Kg7 {good prophylactic move which covers the dark squares around the king}
(17... c5 {is basically a draw offer} 18. dxc5 Qxc5) 18. Rac1 b5 {is more of a
challenge to White} (18... c5 19. dxc5 Qxc5 $11) 19. a3 a5 20. Be4 Rab8 21. Rb1
b4 22. axb4 axb4 $15) 13... Bd6 14. Bf4 {Exchanging one of the bishops is
Black's dream in the position. After doing so, practically his play is much
easier as the knight is free to jump around} Bxf4 15. Qxf4 Rad8) 2. Nc3 d5 3.
Nf3 Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Nbd7 8. Qe2 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4
10. Bxe4 g6 11. c3 (11. O-O {is probably better} Bg7 12. Rb1 O-O 13. d3 $14 {
[%cal Yb2b4,Yb4b5] The pawn on d3 is better placed since Black does not have
breaks against it now}) 11... Bh6 $1 12. h4 Nc5 $1 13. d4 {forcing mass
exchanges} (13. Bc2 Qd5) 13... Bxc1 14. Rxc1 (14. dxc5 Bh6 15. h5 Qg5 {is also
slightly in Black's favor}) 14... Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Qd5 16. Qxd5 (16. f3 Qxa2 {
is just a free pawn} 17. O-O Qd5 $17) 16... cxd5 17. h5 Ke7 18. Kd2 Rhc8 19. a4
Rc6 {The position is realistically equal but Karpov's trademark understanding
and technique proved to be too much for the Serbian grandmaster} 20. a5 b5 21.
axb6 Rxb6 22. Kc2 Rab8 23. Rb1 Rb3 24. hxg6 hxg6 25. f3 a5 26. Rhg1 a4 27. Rh1
g5 28. g4 Kf6 29. Rhe1 R8b7 30. Rh1 Kg6 31. Rhe1 R7b6 32. Rh1 Kf6 33. Rh6+ Ke7
34. Rhh1 Kd6 35. Rhe1 f6 36. Rh1 Rb8 37. Rhe1 e5 38. dxe5+ fxe5 39. Rh1 Kc5 40.
Rhe1 Kc4 41. Rxe5 a3 42. Re7 Rxb2+ 43. Rxb2 Rxb2+ 44. Kc1 Kb3 45. Rb7+ Kxc3 46.
Rc7+ Kd3 47. Ra7 Rb3 48. Ra5 d4 49. Ra4 Kc3 50. Ra5 d3 51. Rc5+ Kb4 0-1

