{[%evp 0,46,32,23,45,49,68,67,68,52,47,27,96,82,70,74,69,50,41,53,41,12,23,23,
8,16,28,6,7,-3,34,17,12,-11,-18,-25,-20,-21,-49,-49,-40,-40,-40,-40,-43,-50,
-51,-53,-58] Another example of a game without light-squared bishops: White's
knights were misplaced but, unfortunately, black offered a draw!} 1. e4 d5 2.
exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Be2 c6 6. Nf3 Bf5 7. O-O e6 8. Ne5 (8. Nh4
Bg6) 8... Nbd7 9. Nc4 Qc7 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 b5 12. Nd2 Be7 {The evaluation
of the position here depends entirely on the activity of the pieces. Black has
a slight advantage in my opinion because the knights interfere with one another
} 13. Nde4 O-O 14. Bg5 Rfe8 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Qf3 {Here,a draw was agreed.
Nonetheless, I believe Black has some practical chances} b4 $1 (16... h6 {
is usually good as Black gets a tempo to open a window for the king} 17. Bf4
Qb6 18. h3 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 Nf6 {Black needs to be careful for tactics though} 20.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. Bxh6 $11 (21. c3 Rd5)) 17. Nxf6+ Nxf6 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Bxe7 Rxe7
(19... Qxe7 $15) 20. Qxe4 Red7 21. Rd3 c5 $17 22. dxc5 Rxd3 23. cxd3 Qxc5 {
Black has all the chances to play for the win without any risk} 1/2-1/2

