9,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-51,-28,-72,-81,-114,-71,-88,-81,-105,-110,-97,-143,-187,-132,
-145,-151,-176,-172,-169,-164] Black missed a favorable transition into the
dxe5 structures} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Bc4
e6 7. Bd2 c6 8. Qe2 Bb4 9. O-O {Not very ambitious. If White wants to claim an
advantage, he should castle queenside} Nbd7 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Qc7 12. Ne5
O-O 13. Rfe1 $2 (13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Rad1 b5 (14... Nd5 15. Bxd5 cxd5 {[%cal
Yf8c8,Yb7b5]}) 15. Bd3 a5 16. Bxf5 $6 {just surrenders the control of the
center to Black} exf5 $15) 13... Rad8 $2 (13... Nxe5 $3 14. dxe5 Ne4 15. Qf3 (
15. Rad1 $4 Nxc3 $19) (15. Bd4 c5 16. Be3 Qxe5 $17) 15... Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Rad8
$15 {There are several weak spots in White's position: e5, c2 and potentitally
b2 as well. No piece can ever occupy d6 so Black is doing dine}) 14. Rad1 Rfe8
(14... Nd5 $1 {is more precise} 15. Bxd5 (15. h3 Nxc3 16. bxc3) (15. Bb3 Nxc3
16. bxc3 Nxe5 (16... Qa5) 17. Qxe5 Qxe5 18. Rxe5 Rd6 {White has stable pressure
}) 15... cxd5) 15. Bd3 Nd5 16. Bd2 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 c5 18. Qf3 Nxe5 19. dxe5 {
Another typical structure that often occurs in the Scandinavian. Black has
better chances in the long run as White's bishop is somewhat restricted by his
own pawns} h6 20. Qg4 Kf8 {escaping the pin} 21. c4 Ne7 22. Bc3 Nf5 23. Qe4 h5
24. h3 h4 25. b4 Kg8 26. b5 Rd7 27. Rxd7 Qxd7 28. Re2 Qd1+ 29. Re1 Qb3 30. Bd2
Rd8 31. Bg5 Rd7 32. Be3 Qxa3 33. Kh2 Kh7 34. Qc2 b6 35. Qe4 Qd3 36. Qc6 Ne7 37.
Qf3 Ng6 38. Qh5+ Kg8 39. Rc1 Qe4 0-1

