{[%evp 0,9,36,21,27,28,23,28,12,5,15,12]} {What should Black's next move be?} 
1... Nc8 $3 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Yc8d6,Yd6f5] Black takes advantage of the lack of
light-squared bishops and the misplaced bishop on g3} (1... Nbd7 2. Rd3 $14) (
1... Nbd5 $6 2. Ne2 $1 $14 {[%cal Yc2c4]}) (1... h6 2. Ne4 Nxe4 3. Qxe4 Qd5) (
1... h6 2. Rfe1 Nbd5 3. Ne4 (3. Rf1 Nxc3 4. Qxc3 Ne4 5. Qe3 Nxg3 6. Qxg3 Bd6 7.
Qe3 Qc7 8. Nf3 Rfd8)) 2. Rfe1 (2. Nc4 Nd6 {Black needs to exchange some pieces
to ease the oressure} 3. Nxd6 Bxd6 4. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11 5. Ne4 $6 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Qd5
$1 {the typical idea} 7. Qxd5 cxd5 8. Rfe1 Rfc8 $15) (2. Ne4 Nxe4 3. Qxe4 Nd6
4. Qe2 Nf5 5. c3 Nxg3 6. hxg3 Bf6) (2. Ne2 {possibly the best} Nd6 (2... Qd5)
3. c4 Nf5 4. Bf4) 2... Nd6 3. Qd3 Nf5 $11 4. Bf4 Nd5 5. Nxd5 cxd5 $15 {[%cal
Ye7f6,Yf6e5] To sum up, the most important ideas of the Scandinavian are the
Nd5 jump and the minority attack, the idea that the heavy piece endgames are
in Black's favor. Development matters a lot in the open centers. A transition
to the dxe5 type of structure is something Black should keep in mind. The
evaluation of the positions without light squared bishops depends entirely on
piece activity} *

