{[%evp 0,84,25,5,49,49,49,41,42,54,94,97,89,87,82,40,28,55,28,-2,18,34,22,26,
26,32,34,31,39,39,39,36,39,32,36,35,37,37,33,16,35,23,34,32,35,31,41,28,34,26,
32,37,52,40,44,32,30,26,31,29,33,49,25,14,1,-10,14,-28,-47,-60,-53,-53,-38,-7,
-24,-85,-89,-109,-99,-167,-170,-164,-171,-265,-286,-29993,-29994]} 1. e4 d5 2.
exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 c6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 {The starting
position of the line} 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O (
12. Rh3 Bg2 13. Rg3 Bd5 {is the other possible line}) 12... Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 {
Everything up to now has been played before and is well-known theory.
Objectively, White is slightly better but by no means is his advantage of
decisive value. Black's position is very solid and has enough resources to
hold. In a potential endgame, Black would have good counter chances and a safe
haven for his king on d6 (if the dark-squared bishops are exchanged)} 14. Bd3
Bd6 15. c3 Qc7 {Memorizing heavy theory is not needed in quiet positions like
this one. Making natural moves and following strategic guidelines is more than
sufficient.} (15... O-O-O $5) (15... g6 $5 {trying to force matters on the
kingside is another possibility}) 16. Qe2 (16. Qf3 {is a better option because
it prevents the trade of bishops}) (16. f4 g6 17. h6 O-O {Black's monarch is
not in danger of an attack. If White commits to f5, he will expose his own
king too much}) 16... Bf4 {Eliminating White's bishop pair} 17. Qf3 Bxc1 18.
Raxc1 O-O 19. Rfe1 h6 20. Kg2 Rfe8 21. Qg3 Qxg3+ 22. Kxg3 a6 {Black implies he
might start a minority attack in the future. However, this is more of an
illusory threat at the moment as b5 does not create any particular trouble} 23.
a4 Rab8 24. Ra1 Kf8 {[%cal Yf8e7,Ye7d6] The king comes to his ideal place in
the center} 25. f4 Ke7 26. Kf3 (26. f5 Kd6 27. fxe6 fxe6 $11 {Exchanging the
pawns does not give White anything: e6 is easily protected. Additionally, now
Black has the option to break with e5 and get a good square for the knight})
26... Kd6 27. Rg1 f6 28. Rgd1 Rbc8 {I believe in a practical game Black is the
one with more chances although the engine prefers White} 29. a5 {[%cal Yd7b8,
Yb8c6] A perfectly logical move at first glance: White fixates the black pawns
on light squares. Nevertheless, I find it inaccurate as after Nb8-Nc6 White is
bound to protect the pawn at all times. Defending a5 with b4 is not a solution
because it makes the c3 pawn a permanent weakness} Re7 30. Ra4 Nb8 31. c4 $6
Nc6 32. Bf1 Kc7 33. f5 (33. cxd5 exd5 $17) 33... e5 34. dxe5 Nxe5+ {White's
position is holding on the edge: in my opinion, only the computer can defend
it successfully} 35. Kg3 dxc4 36. Bxc4 Kb8 37. Be6 $6 {This move appears to be
quite aggressive but in reality, only isolates the bishop! It is now cut off
and unable to aid the defense against Black's threats} Rc2 38. Rb1 (38. b3 Rec7
$19) 38... Rd2 $1 {[%cal Ye7c7,Yc7c2] Black gets ready to put both rooks on
the second rank} (38... Rec7 {gives White an opportunity to improve the
coordination of his pieces} 39. Bd5 (39. Rd4)) 39. b4 Rc7 40. Ra3 (40. Ra2 Rc3+
41. Kf4 Rd4#) 40... Rcc2 41. Rab3 (41. Rg1 Nc6) 41... Rg2+ 42. Kf4 Rce2 {
Checkmate is unavoidable} 0-1

