{[%evp 0,78,19,38,42,37,76,65,68,54,45,43,75,67,73,34,34,10,42,-3,2,-7,-2,8,35,
-36,-43,-41,-33,-45,-45,-55,-57,-61,-50,-76,-81,-78,-78,-88,-56,-63,-58,-55,
-71,-72,-41,-114,-103,-103,-85,-84,-97,-90,-72,-110,-45,-121,-166,-52,-57,-89,
-70,-100,-76,-87,-78,-190,-194,-348,-322,-339,-337,-337,-337,-409,-438,-500,
-497,-2059,-1075] The game illustrates Black's reaction to a setup with d3. It
is a great example of what happens when White's light-squared bishop is
isolated on the queenside while its counterpart stands unopposed on the long
diagonal (h1-a8)} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. d3 c6 6. Bd2
Qc7 7. a3 {too slow} Nbd7 8. Nge2 e6 9. Ng3 (9. Bf4 {is a more logical
decision. However, after} Bd6 {Black develops easily and does not encounter
any opening problems} 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. O-O b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 13. d4 a6 $15 14.
Re1 c5 15. dxc5 Qxd1 (15... Qxc5 $15) 16. Raxd1 Nxc5 17. Ba2 O-O {White's
pieces are lacking coordination}) (9. d4 {is another natural choice} Bd6 10. h3
$6 O-O 11. O-O b6 {Black develops his light-squared bishop on its optimal
place and is then ready to attack the center with either c5 or e5} 12. Re1 Bb7
13. Be3 a6 (13... c5 14. Nb5 Qc6 $17) 14. Bd3 c5 $17) 9... b5 10. Ba2 Bb7 11.
Nge4 a6 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6 $15 13. Qe2 c5 14. f4 Be7 15. O-O O-O 16. Rae1 Rae8 17.
Ne4 Nxe4 18. dxe4 c4 $17 {All White's misfortunes come from the isolated
position of his bishop} 19. c3 f5 20. e5 Rd8 21. Bb1 Rd5 22. Bc2 {Even after
all the maneuvring, the bishop still cannot find its place} Qc6 23. Rd1 Bc5+
24. Kh1 g5 $1 25. Bc1 (25. fxg5 Rxe5 $19 {[%cal Yc6g2]}) 25... Rxd1 26. Rxd1 g4
27. b4 Be7 28. Be3 h5 29. Qf2 Rd8 30. Rxd8+ Bxd8 31. Kg1 Kf7 32. Kf1 h4 33. Bc5
h3 34. g3 Qh1+ 35. Qg1 Qf3+ 36. Qf2 Qxc3 37. Bd4 Qxa3 38. Qd2 Qf3+ 39. Bf2 Qh1+
0-1

