{[%evp 0,94,26,25,36,42,64,44,53,56,68,27,6,42,17,-10,52,46,8,8,8,8,17,-12,-41,
-28,-26,-58,-44,-33,-33,-55,-47,-56,-14,-28,-46,-49,-46,-56,-93,-88,-66,-69,
-76,-82,-84,-76,-92,-183,-151,-155,-186,-186,-107,-160,-134,-144,-125,-138,
-145,-150,-157,-158,-158,-152,-140,-144,-132,-156,-132,-139,-148,-189,-110,
-122,-124,-365,-365,-365,-307,-356,-377,-335,-374,-376,-381,-381,-361,-361,
-212,-221,-243,-772,-787,-29999,-30000] This game gives an example of how to
play actively as Black and use the powerful queen on e5 to create problems for
the opponent. It can also serve as an opening reference due to the added
annotations} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4 {A playable but not very challenging
continuation} (3. Nf3 {After this move, Black immediately gets a chance to
develop in a more aggressive way} Bg4 4. Be2 Nc6 $11 {the best and most played
setup} (4... c6 {Nonetheless, some players like Tiviakov have tested this move
as well. It is considered to be somewhat passive but rather solid. Black is
ready to defend a slightly worse position for a long time and try to swindle
his opponent when the opportunity arises} 5. d4 Nf6 6. c4 Qd6 7. Nc3 e6 $16)) (
3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 (4. Bc4 Nf6 5. d4 Bg4 6. f3 Bd7 7. Nge2 e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Be3
O-O 10. Kh1 Rd8 11. Ng3 $6 c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 $15) 4... e5 $5 {
A risky line which objetively is not the best but good for a surprise or rapid/
blitz} 5. dxe5 Nc6 {Black aims to develop in a fast manner and force White to
play passively} 6. Nf3 (6. Bb5 {is harmless} Bd7) 6... Bb4 ({or} 6... Bg4 {
first}) 7. Bd2 Bg4 8. Be2 $6 O-O-O {White played just one inaccurate move and
Black got an excellent position!} 9. a3 $4 {is close to losing because of
White's crippled structure. Additionally, Black's army is much more active
which is the main factor to consider in positions with an open center} Bxc3 10.
bxc3 Nxe5 $17 {White's situation is tricky to navigate and borderline hopeless
due to the numerous weaknesses. Black will soon occupy the central squares
with his knights and make his opponent suffer for the rest of the game}) 3...
Nc6 (3... e5 {is a viable alternative here} 4. dxe5 Qxe5+ 5. Be2 Bg4 6. Be3
Bxe2 7. Nxe2 Nc6 8. Nbc3 Nf6 $11) 4. Nf3 Bg4 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Yc6d4]} 5. Be2
O-O-O {Black needs to know this position by heart: the good side of it is that
there is not much room for novelties from White} 6. Be3 (6. c3 {is a way to
transpose} e5 7. c4 Qa5+ 8. Bd2 Bb4) 6... e5 {Black's typical break in the
center!} 7. dxe5 $6 {A dubious decision as it allows Black to solve his
opening struggles and achieve a great position} (7. c4 {is the proper
continuation} Qa5+ 8. Bd2 Bb4 9. d5 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd4 $11 {Black has very good
counterplay due to his strong knight}) (7. h3 $2 Bxf3 $17 8. Bxf3 Qa5+ 9. Bd2
Qb6 10. Bxc6 Qxc6 $17 (10... bxc6 {is a bad move here but serves for
illustrative purposes. In the Scandinavian, Black is often open to taking on
c6 with a pawn if he gets activity in exchange. Having the central files under
control coupled with active positions for the queen and minor pieces gives him
enough compensation for the defect in the pawn structure})) 7... Qa5+ $1 8.
Nbd2 Bc5 $1 9. Bxc5 Qxc5 {All the Black pieces are greatly placed and ensure
the pawn on e5 will be recovered soon} 10. O-O (10. c3 {or any other random
move lets Black show his intentions: regaining the pawn while keeping control
over all the squares in the center} Nxe5 11. Nxe5 $2 Qxe5 $19 12. h3 (12. f3
Bf5) 12... Bf5) 10... Nh6 11. Re1 $6 (11. Nb3 Rxd1 (11... Qb6 12. Qe1 $1 Rhe8
13. Qc3 $1 $11) 12. Nxc5 Rxa1 13. Rxa1 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe2 {The fact there are
pawns on the two sides of the board slightly favors Black as the bishop can
switch flanks faster than the knight} 15. Re1 Rd8 16. f3 Bb5 $15) ({or} 11. c3
Rhe8 12. Qc2 Nxe5 $11 {Even though the position is objectively equal, in
practice it is much easier to play as Black as he is the one creating the
threats}) 11... Rhe8 (11... Bxf3 $5 {is another way to continue the game} 12.
Bxf3 Nxe5 13. Nb3 $1 $11 {Black develops naturally and is never in danger}) 12.
Qc1 $6 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 $6 (13. Bxf3 $2 Nxe5 $17 {black is better since all his
pieces are centrally placed}) (13. Nb3 $1 Qb4 14. c3 Qh4 15. Bxf3 Nxe5 16. Be2
Kb8 17. Nd4 $13) 13... Ng4 14. Rf1 Ngxe5 15. Nxe5 $6 $15 Rxe5 16. Bd3 Nb4 $17
17. Qf4 Nxd3 18. cxd3 f6 19. Rac1 $6 Qd4 20. Qg3 Rd7 21. Rc3 Re2 22. Rfc1 c6 $1
(22... Qe5 $6 23. Qxe5 fxe5 $19) 23. Rb3 Rde7 (23... Rxb2 $4 24. Rxc6+ Kd8 $8 {
unclear}) 24. Kf1 $2 (24. h3 $8 Rd2 $1 {[%cal Gg7g6]} 25. Rc4 Re1+ 26. Kh2 Qe5
$17) 24... Rxb2 $19 25. Qf3 (25. Rxc6+ bxc6 26. Qb8+ Kd7 27. Rxb2 (27. Rb7+
Rxb7 $19) 27... Qxd3+ 28. Kg1 Re1#) (25. Ra3 Qc5) 25... Rxb3 26. axb3 Qb2 27.
Qd1 (27. Re1 Rxe1+ 28. Kxe1 $19) 27... Kb8 $6 (27... Re2 $6 28. Rxc6+ bxc6 29.
Qxe2 Qb1+ 30. Qe1 Qxd3+ 31. Kg1 Qxb3 32. h3) (27... Qe5 $1 {[%cal Ge5h2]} 28.
g3 Rd7 {[%cal Ge5d5]} 29. Kg1 Qd4 $19 {[%csl Yd3]}) 28. g3 $17 a6 $1 29. Rc4
Rd7 30. Re4 Qc3 31. Re3 g6 32. h4 f5 33. h5 gxh5 $6 34. Qxh5 Rxd3 35. Re8+ Ka7
36. Qxf5 Qd4 $6 (36... Rd5 $1 37. Qf7 (37. Qxh7 $6 Qf3 38. Re7 Rd1+ 39. Re1 Rd2
40. Qh2 a5 41. Kg1 Rd1 42. Rxd1 Qxd1+ 43. Kg2 Qxb3 $19) 37... Qd3+ 38. Kg2 Rf5
39. Re3 Qxe3 40. Qxf5 Qxb3 41. f4 Kb6 $19 {[%cal Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Ga4a3,Ga3a2,Ga2a1]
}) 37. Qxh7 (37. Re4 $5 Qd5 38. Qxd5 cxd5 39. Rb4 a5 40. Ke2 $3 Rxg3 41. Ra4
