{[%evp 0,38,19,38,42,37,76,65,68,58,58,41,49,41,54,27,27,40,41,-75,-41,-25,-18,
4,0,-71,64,64,92,-81,-74,-318,-347,-365,-215,-29995,-29990,-29991,-29992,
-29993,-29994] A blitz game including a typical but rather easy tactic!} 1. e4
d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Bc4 {Ne5 or Bd2 is more
topical} e6 7. Qe2 $2 {In case White wants to place Qe2, he should do it via
another move order and play Bd2 first} (7. Bd2 Bb4 8. Qe2 $6 O-O $1 (8... Nc6
$4 9. d5) 9. O-O-O $2 (9. a3 Nc6 $1) 9... Nc6 $1 $15 {transposes to the game!})
7... Bb4 8. Bd2 O-O (8... c6 {goes into the Old Main line}) 9. O-O-O $5 Nc6 $1
$15 {Black spared himself the move c6 and went for a more aggressive setup
with Nc6 exploiting White's mix up of move orders} 10. a3 $2 {A tactical
blunder- Black gets a decisive attack after the piece sacrifice} Bxa3 11. bxa3
(11. Na2 Bb4 $1 $19 {Black needs to keep this trick in mind}) 11... Qxa3+ 12.
Kb1 Nb4 $2 (12... b5 $1 $19 {is the precise move}) 13. Rc1 Nfd5 $2 {Generally,
in such positions Black does not need to hurry and look for a direct win.He
has the option to simply maintain the initiative as he is not down too much
material} 14. Nxd5 $4 {White is now unable to reflect all the threats from his
opponent} exd5 15. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 16. Ka1 (16. Bb3 Qxb3+) 16... dxc4 17. Qe5 Qa3+
18. Kb1 c3 19. Qb5 c6 {Guest72071 Ñäàåòñÿ (Lag: Av=0.38s, max=0.8s)} 0-1

