{[%evp 0,94,28,23,37,49,58,41,41,41,41,49,54,54,54,42,76,98,58,48,48,43,37,-5,
-7,0,1,-9,12,-1,1,-1,-2,-13,7,-8,0,-16,-1,3,5,14,22,23,33,-10,17,-20,29,11,20,
32,16,28,27,23,23,14,9,3,6,6,2,-3,-3,-48,-12,-5,21,-11,-6,-17,-11,-62,0,-13,0,
-53,-53,-55,-43,-57,-63,-68,-69,-63,-96,-91,-60,-70,-68,-161,-200,-316,-316,
-358,-366] A typical Scandinavian battle!} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4.
d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 {The new main line} 6. Bc4 (6. Bd3) (6. Ne5 c6 {the only
move here} 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 e6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 {White is slightly
better due to his faster development but Black's position is solid enough})
6... e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6 10. O-O (10. Qe2 {is the other choice
}) (10. d5 {is good but simplifies the position a lot}) 10... O-O {The
computer might claim the position to be slightly better for White (+0.4) but
that is of little practical value. No human can consistently play the engine's
top choice even at the elite GM level. Black has enough activity and is
nowhere close to being outplayed. I believe the position is equal and both
sides have chances} (10... Nc6 11. d5 O-O-O) 11. Ne5 $6 {This idea is hardly
ever good as Black is able to counter it with} Nc6 $1 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Bd3 (
13. Qe2 Nd5 {is always a good choice too} (13... Bxc2 $2 14. Bb4) 14. Bxd5 (14.
Rad1 Bxc2 (14... Nxc3 15. bxc3)) 14... exd5 {Black's position is a tad
preferable as his bishop is more active for the moment. The plan is to follow
up with Rfe8, Qg6 and apply pressure eventually going for a kingside attack}
15. Qd2 Qg6 16. Rac1 Rfe8 17. Rfe1 h5 {[%cal Yh4h3] White is the only one who
can be in danger here}) 13... Be4 (13... Rad8 14. Bxf5 exf5 15. Re1 Nd5 $15 {
The knight is much stronger than the bishop and controls all the light squares
in the center}) 14. Bxe4 (14. f3 {After provoking the f3 weakening Black is
ready to exchange the bishops} Bxd3 $15 15. Qxd3 Rad8 16. Rad1 Nd5 $15 (16...
Rd5 {A standard idea: Black puts all his heavy pieces on the d file and
threatens to take the d4 pawn after e5 or c5. This reflects Black's main
strategic goal in the Scandinavian: a slow and long endgame with a slight edge}
) 17. Bd2) 14... Nxe4 15. Qd3 Rfd8 (15... Nxc3 $1 {Black destroys White's
structure and as a result has preferable chances in the endgame}) 16. Rfe1 Nf6
$2 {A surprising decision! It is much more natural to spoil White's pawn
structure with Nxc3!} (16... Nxc3 $1 $17 17. bxc3 {It is hard to play a bad
move as Black} Rd6 (17... Qa4 18. Re5 b6 $15 {[%cal Yc7c5]}) (17... Qd6 $15 {
[%cal Yc7c5]}) 18. c4 Rad8 19. c3 b6 $15) 17. Bd2 Qd6 (17... b5 {А typical
way to secure the d5 square for thr knight. Unfortunately, it does not work
here as White is just in time to play Bg5 and exchange the minor pieces} 18.
Bg5 (18. Bc3 {for illustrative purposes} Nd5 19. Bd2 {retreating the bishop
and threatening to play b3 and c4} Qc4 $1 {Black stops c4 by force! The
powerful knight on d5 cannot be evicted anymore! The c4 and c7 pawns cannot be
attacked} 20. Qxc4 bxc4 21. Rad1 Rab8 22. Bc1 Rd6 23. c3 f6 $15 {[%cal Yg7g5,
Yg8f7] Black starts to gain space on the kingside} 24. g3 (24. f3) 24... g5 25.
Kg2 h5 26. Re2 Kf7 {Black has a very stable advantage: his strategic ideas are
to play c5, open the d file and exchange the rooks getting a bad bishop vs a
good knight endgame} (26... c5 27. Ree1 (27. dxc5 Ne3+) 27... Rc8 28. dxc5 Rxc5
29. Rd2 Rcc6 30. Kf1 Kf7 31. Ree2 Nb6 32. Rxd6 Rxd6 $17 33. Rd2 Rxd2 34. Bxd2
a5 35. Ke2 a4 36. Ke3 e5))) 18. Be3 Ng4 (18... Qc6 {is another idea} 19. Qd2 a6
20. Bf4 Nh5 21. Bg3 Nxg3 22. hxg3 {The doubled pawns might be a disadvantage
in the future}) 19. g3 Qd5 (19... Nxe3 {is probably the way to go. Black
secures a slightly more pleasant endgame} 20. fxe3 c5 21. c3 h5 $15 {[%cal
Yh5h4] addressing White's weak king}) 20. Qe2 Qf5 21. c3 Rd7 (21... Nxe3 {
is an oversimplification and offers less chances for a win} 22. Qxe3 c6 23. Qe5
Qg6 24. Re2 Rd7 25. Rae1 Rad8 26. Kg2 h6 27. Qf4 Qd3 28. Qd2 Qc4 29. Qe3 b6 {
Black is ready to push c5 and gain control of the only open file thus
obtaining an edge} (29... Rd5)) 22. Kg2 Rad8 23. h3 Nf6 24. Qf3 Qb5 25. a4 Qd5
26. Qxd5 Nxd5 27. a5 f6 28. Ra3 a6 29. Rb3 c6 30. Kf3 Kf7 31. h4 Rc8 32. Re2 h6
33. Re1 g5 34. hxg5 hxg5 35. Rh1 Kg6 36. c4 Ne7 37. g4 Re8 38. Rh5 Nf5 39. Rh1
Nd6 40. Rc3 f5 41. gxf5+ exf5 42. d5 f4 43. Bb6 Ne4 44. Rd3 Kf5 45. Rh5 Nf6 46.
Rh6 Ng4 47. Rh5 Ne5+ 0-1

