{[%evp 0,96,27,13,39,36,48,48,49,48,48,50,56,34,80,61,77,38,73,35,28,17,11,-12,
-16,-44,-59,-62,-55,-53,-76,-61,-77,-72,-50,-72,-77,-84,-62,-159,-62,-85,-55,
-69,-76,-87,-90,-86,-63,-81,-110,-92,-104,-137,-116,-130,-143,-137,-118,-148,
-148,-141,-163,-158,-150,-180,-111,-109,-108,-195,-157,-258,-234,-234,-209,
-215,-196,-269,-315,-315,-369,-369,-369,-369,-448,-557,-592,-629,-551,-575,
-634,-666,-681,-657,-675,-820,-843,-843,-883]} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6
(3... Qa5 {similar position might be achieved via} 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. d3 {The
disadvantage of this move is that with the pawn on d3, playing d5 is never an
option for White} e6 {Black transposes to a French-style structure} (5... Bf5 {
This plan is not working fine for Black anymore: Bf5 is restricted by the d3
pawn and in the event of the typical Bb4, Bxc3 White's dark-squared bishop
will not be blocked by the d pawn} 6. Nge2 e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 $16
) (5... Bg4 {is playable} 6. f3 Bd7 (6... Bh5 {is very passive and not
recommended} 7. Nge2 e6 8. O-O)) 6. Bd2 Nbd7 (6... c6 {is not Black dreams of;
White holds the initiative} 7. Nd5 Qd8 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Bc3 $14) 7. Nf3 (7. Nd5
Qc5 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6 9. Nf3 b5 $1 {By playing this move, Black isolates his
opponent's bishop on b3 where it is not doing anything} (9... Qd6 10. O-O c6
11. d4 b5 12. Bb3 (12. Bd3)) 10. Bb3 Bb7 11. O-O Bd6 12. d4 (12. Be3 Qh5) 12...
Qb6 13. Re1 O-O (13... c5 $15) 14. Be3 c5 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Bxc5 Qxc5 $11) 7...
c6 8. O-O (8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Nxf6+ Nxf6 10. O-O b5 11. Bb3 Bd6 12. a4 O-O 13. Re1
Bb7 14. Bg5 a6 15. Ne5 Qc7 $15 {[%cal Yc6c5] Taking on f6 is not dangerous})
8... Qc7 9. Re1 (9. a4 b6 10. d4 {White has given Black enough time to develop
comfortably. For example,} Bd6 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Re1 Bb7 (12... a6 13. Ne4 Nxe4
14. Bxe4 Nf6 15. Bd3 c5 16. dxc5 Bxc5)) 9... b5 {Again the same idea: forcing
White's bishop to an unpleasant square} 10. Bb3 (10. Bxe6 {does not work since
Black has enough resources to comfortably defend} fxe6 11. Rxe6+ Be7 12. Qe2
Nf8 13. Re3 Ng6) 10... Bd6 11. d4 O-O 12. a3 Bb7 13. h3 a6 $17 {[%cal Yc6c5,
Ya6b5]} 14. Qe2 (14. a4 b4 $17) (14. Bg5 c5 15. dxc5 Bxc5 ({Even} 15... Nxc5 {
is playable since Bb3 is completely out of play} 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Ba2 Rad8 18.
Qe2 f5 $19)) 14... c5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 $17) 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 a6 6. Be2 Nbd7 (6...
Nc6 7. d5 Nb4 8. Bc4 b5 9. Bb3 Bb7 $11) 7. Be3 e6 8. Qd2 Be7 9. h3 b5 {Black
can afford such a move because White developed rather passively and lost a lot
of tempi with Be2,Be3, h3 etc} 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. Bf4 Qb6 12. Qe2 c5 {Black got a
great version of a French Defense structure} 13. dxc5 Nxc5 $17 {[%cal Yb7g2]
Black is already better: he manages to eliminate White's light-squared bishop
and eye the White king with its counterpart} 14. a3 Nxd3+ (14... O-O) 15. Qxd3
O-O 16. O-O Qc6 {A long-term pin that does not let White move his knight from
f3 (due to mate on g2)} (16... Rfd8 17. Qe2 Rac8 $17) 17. Rad1 Rac8 18. Rfe1 h6
19. Qf1 Qb6 $17 {Black has a tremendous advantage} 20. Qd3 (20. Rd2 Bxf3 $19)
20... Qc6 21. Be5 Rfd8 22. Qf1 Nd7 23. Rd3 f6 24. Bg3 e5 25. Nd5 Bf8 26. b4
Qxc2 (26... Nb6 27. Nxb6 Qxb6 $19) 27. Ne3 Qa2 28. Red1 Qe6 29. Nh4 Be4 30.
R3d2 g5 31. Nf3 Be7 (31... Bxf3 32. gxf3) 32. Nh2 f5 (32... Nb6) 33. f3 Bb7 34.
Bf2 Nf6 35. g4 Rxd2 36. Rxd2 f4 37. Nf5 Bf8 38. h4 e4 39. Bc5 Rxc5 40. bxc5
Bxc5+ 41. Kg2 exf3+ 42. Nxf3 Nxg4 43. Rd8+ Kh7 44. Qd3 Qa2+ 45. Qd2 Qxd2+ 46.
Rxd2 Ne5 47. Rc2 Bxf3+ 48. Kf1 Nc4 0-1

