{[%evp 0,132,27,13,36,48,50,50,68,67,75,64,91,49,63,51,92,71,49,37,43,45,41,39,
25,33,32,28,47,44,36,-2,22,18,17,0,0,0,0,-2,0,-14,-8,-2,-19,-4,-10,-67,-75,-93,
-53,-89,-84,-68,-19,-26,-74,-47,-47,-75,-56,-65,-74,-47,-50,-50,-50,-48,-48,
-57,-68,-86,-88,-92,-75,-62,-82,-87,-93,-95,-68,-124,-58,-56,-58,-71,-64,-70,
-50,-44,-46,-46,-28,-15,0,0,-9,-5,-22,0,-32,-96,-104,-106,-97,-110,-109,-132,
-122,-116,-149,-146,-156,-151,-142,-205,-190,-198,-165,-192,-210,-196,-220,
-210,-292,-261,-323,-341,-356,-464,-472,-712,-722,-732,-742] One of the
advantages of the Scandinavian is that there are not that many lines where
White can deviate and produce a viable novelty. Black needs to know a couple
of ideas and he should not be too concerned about long forced lines} 1. e4 d5
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 {our main
line of interest} 8. a3 (8. Qe2 Nc6 9. a3 O-O-O 10. O-O-O Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Qb6 $11
) 8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6 10. O-O (10. Qe2 O-O 11. O-O Nc6) (10. d5 $1 {is best
in my opinion}) 10... Nc6 $1 11. b4 (11. d5 $2 O-O-O $17) (11. a4 a5) 11... a6
(11... Bg4 12. h3 (12. Be2 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 O-O-O $17 14. Bxc6 Qxc6) 12... Bxf3
13. Qxf3 O-O-O $132) 12. Qe2 (12. Bb2 $1 {preparing c4 little by little}) (12.
Re1 O-O 13. h3 Rfd8 14. Bb2 Ne7 $16) 12... O-O 13. Bb2 (13. Rad1 Bg4) (13. h3
Nd5 14. Bxd5 $6 exd5 15. Ne5 f6 16. Nxc6 Qxc6 17. Bb2 Kh8 18. c3 $15) 13... Bg4
$5 {Placing the bishop on a more active position and posing concrete problems
for White} (13... Ne7 14. Bb3 Ng6 $132 {seems to be working very well due to
the White queen's position on e2!}) 14. Rad1 Rad8 15. Bb3 Qb5 $3 $15 16. c4 (
16. Qxb5 {as always results in Black gaining excellent control of the light
squares in the center} axb5 17. Rfe1 (17. Rd3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Nd5 $17 {[%csl Rc4,
Yd4,Yf2,Yf3,Rf4,Yh2] White has too many weak squares in his camp; his bishops
are also blocked}) 17... Bxf3 18. gxf3 Nd5 $17) (16. Rd3 $6 Bf5 17. Rd2 Qxe2
18. Rxe2 Bg4 19. c3 b5) 16... Qh5 $15 {Black successfully transferred his
queen and is ready to ruin White's pawn structure on the next move} 17. h3 Bxf3
18. Qxf3 Qxf3 19. gxf3 Ne7 20. a4 (20. d5 exd5 21. Bxf6 gxf6 22. cxd5 Nf5 $15 {
[%cal Yf5d6,Yf8e8]}) 20... Rd7 21. b5 Rfd8 22. Bc2 Ne8 {Black maneuvered his
pieces well and gradually won the game} 23. Kh1 axb5 24. axb5 Nd6 25. Bd3 Ndf5
26. Be4 c6 27. bxc6 bxc6 28. Rd2 Nxd4 29. Rfd1 c5 30. Ba3 Rc8 31. Bxc5 Rxc5 32.
Rxd4 Rxd4 33. Rxd4 f5 34. Bd3 Nc6 35. Rd6 Ne5 36. Be2 Kf7 37. Rd4 g5 38. f4
gxf4 39. Rxf4 Nc6 40. Bf3 Na5 41. Be2 Nb3 42. Rh4 Kg6 43. Bd1 Nd2 44. Rd4 Ne4
45. Kg2 e5 46. Rd5 Rxd5 47. cxd5 Kg5 48. Kf3 Nd6 49. Bc2 h6 50. Kg3 f4+ 51. Kf3
Kh4 52. Kg2 e4 53. Bd1 h5 54. Bb3 f3+ 55. Kh2 Kg5 56. h4+ Kxh4 57. Bc2 Kg4 58.
Bd1 Kf4 59. Kh3 Nf5 60. Bc2 Ke5 61. Bb3 Nd4 62. Bc4 Ne2 63. Kh4 Nf4 64. Bb3 Nd3
65. Kg3 h4+ 66. Kxh4 e3 0-1

[Event "Panormo GRE"]
[Site "Panormo GRE"]
