[White "THEORY THE b4-b5 lines, Ioannis"]
[Black "Papaioannou, Ioannis"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B01"]
[WhiteElo "2310"]
[BlackElo "2520"]
[Annotator "GM Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "92"]
[EventDate "1998.10.24"]

{THE b2-b4 systems! The most critical and common idea that you should know is
that after White's push b4-b5 followed by b5-bc6, Black could play bxc6! and
always get an excellent game! Of course, Qxc6 is also possible if the position
allows it.} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Nf3 Nf6 {For the moment, we
are being flexible with this knight move.} (4... c6 {would be very premature
as, suddenly, he could take the game to the mainline with} 5. d4 {In the
mainline, we want to put our knight to c6.}) {THIS IS THE GAME 
Simeonidis-Papaioannou 1998} 5. Be2 ({If he goes} 5. b4 {now, it is a gambit.
We will take it, we will be patient, and win the game, for example} Qxb4 6. Rb1
Qd6 {A setup with e6 and Be7 should be good enough.} 7. d4 ({I often see White
players play} 7. Bc4 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gc4f7] which is a horrible move because the
bishop doesn't belong there. They get the impression to play d4, Ne5 and win
the f7 pawn but this is not happening. We will play} e6 8. O-O Be7 9. d4 O-O {
We will stabilize the position. The bishop would be much better placed on d3
rather than on c4. Here Black has an extra pawn with some compensation but not
enough for a real game over the board. However, for a blitz game, this is 100%
playable.}) 7... e6 8. Bd3) (5. g3 $1 {Is a playable system. Black has
different options like 5...c6 followed by Bg4 or Bf5 or 5... g6, even the
strange-looking 5...e5!?.} c6 $5 (5... e5 $1 {e7-e5! ... very rare idea in the
Scandinavian!} 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O (7. d3 c6 $1 8. O-O (8. Bd2 {is too passsive}
Qc7) (8. Nd2 {is logical, but Black can face it with} Qd8 $1 9. Nc4 Bc7 $132)
8... O-O 9. Re1 Re8 10. Bd2 Qc7 11. a3 Bg4 12. b4 Nbd7 $132 {Black completes
the development and has a nice game.}) 7... O-O 8. Re1 (8. d3 c6 {transposes
to 7.d3}) 8... Nc6 $1 (8... c6 $6 9. d4 $1 $16 {we should play c6 only If
White chooses the setup with d3}) 9. d3 h6 10. Bd2 Qb6 11. Rb1 a5 $132 ({or} 
11... Bg4 $132)) 6. Bg2 Bf5 (6... Bg4 {Is another possible setup} 7. h3 Bh5 8.
O-O e6 9. d3 Nbd7 10. Bd2 Qc7 11. Rb1 Bd6 12. b4 O-O 13. b5 Rac8 14. bxc6 bxc6
$1 $132 {as we already know, this structure is fully acceptable for Black.}) 7.
O-O e6 8. d3 Be7 9. Bd2 Qd8 $1 (9... Qc7 $5 {Looks more logical, but sometimes
the queen can be under attack here after Bf4.} 10. Rb1 (10. Nh4 Bg4 {is just
fine for Black.}) 10... O-O 11. b4 Nbd7 12. b5 e5 13. bxc6 bxc6 $132) 10. Rb1
a5 $1 $132 {Black has nothing to worry about}) 5... c6 $1 {If White plays
passively, we will most likely follow a setup with c6! followed by Bf5 or Bg4
and then e6! In these positions we are not playing Nc6. The Nc6 setup is good
only in the Neo Scandinavian} 6. O-O {Which move is better now, Bf5 or Bg4?
They are more or less the same.} Bf5 $1 (6... Bg4 $5 7. d4 Nbd7 8. a3 e6 9. Rb1
Bd6 10. b4 Qc7 11. h3 Bh5 12. b5 O-O 13. bxc6 Qxc6 $1 $15 (13... bxc6 $1 $15))
{The moment to play b4 is right here.} 7. b4 ({If he loses one tempo} 7. d4 {
then, we of course, play} e6 {and we develop our pieces.} 8. Bd2 Qc7 {once
again...the ...so very common ..random play by White! ...we get very nice,
healthy and fighting positions..by just playing natural moves!} 9. Nh4 (9. Re1
$6 Bd6 10. h3 h6 $3 $15 {white has been very slow with his play! .. .we can
undoubtedly afford to play an h7-h6!! move...to preserve the Bishop !}) 9...
Bg6 10. Re1 Bd6 11. g3 O-O 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Bf3 Nbd7 $132) 7... Qd8 {The idea
behind this move was to stop any Nd4 moves. But now, I am not sure that this
was correct.} ({Possibly} 7... Qc7 {was better. I should not have worried of
Nd4 moves because I am standing perfectly well. This is, once again, not a
matter of theory, it is a matter of attitude toward the opening.} 8. d3 e6 9.
b5 {Once again, I develop my pieces.} Bd6 10. h3 O-O ({In fact,} 10... h6 {
is interesting.}) {There are ideas like} 11. Nh4 {but they are not so worrying.
We can always play Bg6 with a good game.} Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. a4 {and once
again, we play} Nbd7 {and keep the tension.} ({How about} 13... c5 {? No, this
is not a good idea because} 14. Bf3 {[%cal Gf3a8] this diagonal can be very
annoying.} (14. a5 {[%csl Ga5,Gb5] These pawns are becoming annoying as well.})
) {When he takes} 14. bxc6 ({If he goes} 14. a5 {now possibly we are ready to
take on b5 and also consider a6. But there is no real threat, and we can even
play} Be5 {for example. There is no real threat. White has lost way too much
time with this b4-b5, a4-a5-a6, there are way too many moves. So, we organize
our position and stand perfectly.}) {we will very seriously consider} 14...
bxc6 {and this is an excellent and playable position. For example,} 15. Bf3 ({
A common idea is to give a check and play Bf4. For example,} 15. Bd2 Bh2+ {
[%cal Gh2f4]}) 15... Rab8) 8. b5 e6 {No time for other moves.} 9. Bb2 ({
Now if he takes on c6} 9. bxc6 $2 {I will most likely take with my knight.}
Nxc6 $15 10. Bb5 {What I know for sure is that I am not worried at all. I can
even play Rc8 here but if} Be7 {was forced, I have no problem with that
because we already know that} 11. Ne5 Qc7 12. Nxc6 bxc6 {this setup is, in
fact, totally acceptable for Black.}) 9... Be7 {I develop. I very strongly
support simple chess. So this is the move. You won't see anything tremendous
by me in the very first moves.} ({How about} 9... Nbd7 {? No, this is
premature because he will take it} 10. bxc6 bxc6 {and he will play} 11. Nd4 {
with a double threat.}) ({How about} 9... c5 {? Absolutely not! This is a huge
mistake. This b5-pawn is, in fact, very annoying, and if the bishop can get to
the h1-a8 diagonal, it will be very annoying as well. For example,} 10. d4 {
can be a move, and, all of a sudden, if I play} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bg6 12. Bf3 {
[%csl Rb7] I begin to feel the pressure with the b7-pawn.}) 10. Nh4 Bg6 11. a4
O-O 12. Nxg6 hxg6 {In fact, I can say that I regretted the move Qd8 and Qc7
would have been simply better.} 13. Bf3 {I had to realize my mistake and play}
Qc7 (13... a6 $1 14. bxc6 Nxc6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 $15) 14. d3 Nbd7 {Objectively
speaking, White might vary slightly be better.} 15. g3 Rad8 {But the position
is totally playable.} 16. Qe2 Nd5 17. Ne4 N7f6 18. Ng5 Rfe8 19. Bg2 a6 20. bxc6
bxc6 {White was, indeed, slightly better but in the end I started taking over.
