1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. d3 e6 $1 {This is a very
interesting idea. Black plans to play a well-timed c6-b5. With White's pawn on
d3 instead of d4, the bishop could be isolated on the "b3" square. The scheme
you need to remember is that we always meet 5.d3 with e6 and then after 6.Bd2
we play Nbd7 followed by c6. If White chooses the system with 6.Nf3 then we
should answer with 6...a6 followed by b5 or Qh5 and b5. An important rule in
this position is that we shouldn't be afraid to go for b5, but we should
always calculate the sacrifice Bxe6.} 6. Bd2 (6. Nf3 {Here is an amazingly
strong move:} a6 $3 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] you must remember this great move here!
} 7. O-O (7. Bd2 {now it is this great idea:} Qh5 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7]
Intending b5 and Bb7. This is, again, very good.} (7... Qb6 $5 8. O-O Be7 9.
Bb3 c5 $132) 8. O-O (8. d4 c5 9. Be2 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qe5 11. Be3 Qc7 $132) 8...
b5 9. Bb3 Bb7 $15 {[%cal Gb7f3,Gb8d7,Gf8d6] Now Black is already better,
according to the computer. We want to take on f3 or simply develop the pieces.}
10. Ng5 Qxd1 11. Raxd1 Nbd7 {Black is already better.} 12. Rfe1 Nc5 {At a good
moment, we will take the bishop. This is a very common problem in many
variations also in the Sicilian. The bishop is isolated on b3. Normally, we
should not take it when it is a bad piece. No. But, we do take it and get a
permanent advantage.}) (7. a4 $6 {is well met by} b5 ({It is also possible to
develop the pieces in another way} 7... b6 $5 8. Bd2 Bb4 $132)) 7... b5 8. Bb3
Bb7 {We don't worry about our queen because it has a very safe spot on b6.} 9.
Re1 Nbd7 10. d4 Bd6 (10... b4 $5 {is also very ambitious} 11. Na4 Bd6 $36 12.
c4 (12. Bd2 Ne4 (12... Qh5)) 12... bxc3 13. Nxc3 O-O $15) 11. Ne5 (11. d5 Nc5)
11... O-O $132) 6... Nbd7 $3 {I am providing you with some illustrative lines
here, you don't need to memorize them. The ideas are more important than the
concrete theory.} 7. Nf3 (7. Nf3 c6 8. O-O Qc7 9. Re1 b5 (9... Bd6 $5) 10. Bb3
(10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Rxe6+ Kf7 {Black definitely has some compensation, but not
more than that.}) 10... Bd6 $132 {x Bb3} 11. Ne4 (11. Nd4 O-O $17) 11... Nxe4
12. dxe4 O-O $11) (7. Qf3 Ne5 (7... c6 {is also possible} 8. O-O-O Qc7 9. Nge2
Bd6 10. d4 O-O {with a typical position for this line, which is approximately
equal}) 8. Qe2 Nxc4 9. dxc4 {The position is close to equal. An illustrative
line can be} Bd7 10. Nd5 Qc5 11. Bb4 Qc6 12. Bxf8 Rxf8 13. O-O-O Nxd5 14. cxd5
Qa4 $11) (7. Nge2 {is not very ambitious} c6 8. O-O Qc7 9. Bf4 Bd6 10. Bxd6
Qxd6 11. a4 b6 12. Qd2 O-O $11 13. a5 $6 b5 14. Bb3 a6 15. Rad1 c5 $15) (7. Nb5
{looks dangerous, but Black is just fine after} Qb6 8. a4 (8. Be3 Bc5 $11) 8...
a6 (8... c6) 9. Nc3 (9. a5 $4 Qc6 $17) 9... Ne5 10. Bb3 Bd7 11. a5 Qc6 $11) (7.
Nd5 Qc5 8. Bb4 (8. Nxf6+ Nxf6 {We get this type of French kind of game.} 9. Nf3
{Again,} b5 {with a perfect game for Black.} 10. Bb3 Bb7 {We need to play b5
very fast and isolate that bishop.}) 8... Qc6 $15 9. Bxf8 (9. Nxf6+ $4 gxf6 $3
10. Bxf8 Qxg2 $19) 9... exd5 10. Bxg7 Rg8 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. Bb3 a5 13. a4 Rxg2
14. Qf3 Rg6 15. O-O-O Be6 $15) (7. Qe2 c6 (7... Qe5 $5) 8. O-O-O Qc7 9. Nf3 (9.
Bxe6 {doesn't work here} fxe6 10. Qxe6+ Be7 11. Re1 Nb6 $19) 9... b5 10. Bxe6
fxe6 11. Qxe6+ Be7 12. Rhe1 Nb6 13. Qb3 a5 14. a3 a4 $19 (14... b4 $5 $19)) (7.
Ne4 {is pointless} Qb6 $36) 7... c6 {[%cal Ga5c7]} 8. O-O (8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Nxf6+
Nxf6 10. d4 (10. O-O {Is also possible, but Black can answer it} b5 11. Bb3 Bb7
12. a4 Bd6 13. d4 O-O 14. Qe2 a6 15. Rad1 Qc7 $11) 10... a6 (10... c5 {is
another possibility} 11. Be3 Qc7 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Nxd7 14. d5 exd5 15.
Qxd5 Nf6 $11) 11. O-O c5 12. Be3 Qc7 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Bxc5 Qxc5 15. Bb3 b6 16.
Qe2 Bb7 17. Ne5 O-O {This structure is typical for French Defense with 3.Nd2,
Black has nothing to worry about}) (8. Qe2 Qc7 9. O-O-O $2 b5 $17 10. Bxe6 (10.
Bb3 a5 $15) 10... fxe6 11. Qxe6+ Be7 12. Rhe1 (12. Ng5 Ne5 $19 13. Qb3 h6 $19)
12... Nc5 13. Qe2 b4 14. Nb1 Nd5 15. Bg5 Ne6 $19) 8... Qc7 $132 9. Re1 (9. a4
b6 10. Qe2 Bd6 11. Rfe1 (11. Nd4 Bxh2+ 12. Kh1 Be5) 11... O-O 12. d4 Bb7 13.
Ne5 a6 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 {is about equal}) {It is essential to play} 9... b5 {
to isolate his bishop there.} 10. Bb3 ({Of course, we will calculate} 10. Bxe6
fxe6 11. Rxe6+ {but it hardly ever works.} Be7 12. Qe2 {We protect everything
with} Nf8 $15) 10... Bd6 11. a4 (11. Ng5 {such ideas are not working.} Nc5 {
protects everything.}) (11. d4 {If he plays such move we castle.} O-O 12. Qe2
Bb7 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gc6c5] and a6 and c5. After a few moves, we take over the
