{[%evp 0,40,26,22,38,45,49,61,48,68,62,54,55,83,58,47,53,56,46,25,27,39,26,47,
34,37,24,24,34,42,24,30,6,2,-9,-15,5,-10,-10,-31,-31,-31,-14] this is the game
Ivan Saric 2638-Papaioannou 2606 ISTAMBUL OLYMPIAD 2012} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5
3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bd2 {The moves 5.Bd2 and 5.Bc4 will most likely
transpose to the same position. Of course, in all these lines there are
hundreds of possible moves for White that are less ambitious. What do we do?
Do I need to memorize everything? Absolutely not. I need to keep in my mind
the basic principles of the Scandinavian.} (5. Bc4 Bg4 $1 6. f3 (6. Nge2 $5
Nbd7 7. f3 Bf5 8. Bd2 Qb6) 6... Bd7 7. Bd2 Qb6 {transposition}) 5... Bg4 $1 {
This is a critical position. You can reach it also with the 5.Bc4 move order!}
6. f3 Bd7 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gc7c5,Ga5b6] Maybe intending e6 and c5 and all of this.
Or maybe Qb6. This best move for White will be} 7. Bc4 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5] This
is the correct move.} (7. Nb5 $2 {Of course, this is not something great.} Qb6
$17 8. a4 a6 9. Nc3 (9. a5 $4 Qe6+ 10. Ne2 Bxb5 $19) 9... Qxd4 $19 (9... Nc6
$19)) (7. Bd3 $2 {Very instructive mistake} Nc6 $3 8. Nge2 e5 $3 $17 9. Nb5 Nb4
$17) (7. f4 $5 {is a rare, but interesting continuation} Qb6 8. Nf3 e6 $132 9.
Bd3 Na6 10. a3 c5 {and Black is just fine}) {and now we need to play} 7... Qb6
$1 {In this system, Black is trying to push c7-c5 in a moment when the reply
d4-d5 is not very good for White. If we can achieve this then Black's position
is always better ( after dxc5 or cxd4), because of the terrible combination of
Nge2 and f3.} 8. Nge2 e6 $1 {Taking on b2 is very risky. I think the computer
kind of likes it but we won't be able to back it up.} (8... Nc6 $4 9. Na4 $18)
{Now he must play} 9. Be3 ({Generally speaking, when he plays} 9. a4 {we play}
a5 {[%cal Gb8a6] followed by Na6 at some moment.} 10. Be3 {Do I need to
remember everything by heart here? Absolutely not. Otherwise, I will spend my
whole time studying lines of the Scandinavian.} Be7 {According to the computer,
this is the best move.} ({However, we do know} 10... Na6 {ideas. What do we do
during the game? We will calculate.} 11. Bf2 {He wants to play d5, but it is
not really a threat, we will play Bc5.} Nb4 12. d5 Bc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. dxe6 {
I can possibly even take on c4 but, to me,} fxe6 {is already good enough.} ({Or
} 14... Bxe6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 {this. We already are out of book but I see a well
established knight on b4. I see that he cannot castle short, Qd4 is not
possible as he blunders the queen, Nd4 is not possible because I take Qxd4,
next move might be Rd8 but we see that Black is better.})) 11. Bf2 Na6 $132) (
9. Bb3 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5] Be careful not to blunder your queen. Watch out
for the move Na4, before you play Nc6.} 10. Be3 (10. Na4 Qa6 {[%cal Gc6a5] A
very, very typical idea is putting the queen on a6 when his bishop is on b3.
If necessary, I put my queen on a6 when his knight is on a4 and my next move
is Na5. We are already way out of book. For example,} 11. c4 Na5 {and we get a
fine game.} 12. Bxa5 Qxa5+ 13. Nac3 {We are out of book but we have a nice
advantage of the two bishops.} Be7 {Our queen is safe, we castle, and we get a
perfectly playable position.}) 10... Na5 11. Qd2 {But I know d5 is not really
a threat but I will go Bc5.} Be7 {According to the theory, this is good.} (
11... c5) ({And} 11... Bb4 $1 {is also very good, with a great game for Black.
For example,} 12. O-O (12. d5 {I will calculate. I will consider either Bc5 or}
Nxb3 13. axb3 Bc5 14. Bxc5 Qxc5 15. dxe6 Bxe6 {and once again, we have a great
game.}) 12... O-O $36) 12. d5 Qa6 $15 13. dxe6 Bxe6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 $3) ({
Be careful not to mix things. A very, very important rule to remember: You
need to think - not try every time to imitate the moves of theory. You need to
be 100% sure. For example, if he goes} 9. a3 {and I say "ah, yes, I remember a
move Nc6-e7 somehow" and I play.} Nc6 $4 ({I would possibly consider} 9... c5)
({or maybe a move like} 9... Be7 {first. It is not only about memorizing, it
is also about understanding.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Kh1 c5 $3 $15 12. dxc5 (12. d5
exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bf6 15. Bc3 Bxc3 16. Nxc3 Nc6 $36) 12... Bxc5 (
12... Qxc5)) 10. Na4 $18 {This is a handshake. We need to think. We cannot
memorize everything, not in the Scandinavian, not anywhere else. We need to
think, we need to calculate, and we need to remember the basic principles.})
9... Nc6 $1 {Most likely Black's next move will be Na5!} 10. Qd2 (10. a3 $1 {
[%cal Gc3a4] now he is threatening Na4. Here is one thing you need to know:}
Ne7 $3 {This is another typical idea.} 11. O-O {If you want to learn
everything perfectly} Ng6 $1 {is good.} (11... Ned5 {This move is condemned by
the computer. The computer says that with accurate moves, White can gain an
advantage. But if you play that during a game, your opponent will totally be
unable to find the best moves. Will he know them by heart? There is a
possibility of one in a million. Ivan Saric didn't know it and didn't find it.}
12. Bf2 Be7 13. Ne4 (13. Bxd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Nf4 {and we have a good
game.} Be6 16. Re1 O-O 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Qe2 Rf6 {White is probably slightly
better, but we still have counterplay}) 13... Bb5 {We are already way out of
book.} 14. b3 Bxc4 15. bxc4 Nxe4 16. fxe4 Nf6 {This is a very nice unclear
position.} 17. Nc3 O-O {He has the center but this center is also vulnerable.}
18. Qe2 Qa5 $1 19. Qd3 {and I started attacking his pieces.} Rad8 (19... Ng4
20. Be1 $14) 20. h3 $6 Nd7 $13 21. Rfb1 Ne5 $5 ({I should have played} 21... b6
$15) 22. Qg3 Nxc4 23. Rb5 $1 Qa6 24. Qxc7 Nd6 {and, in the end, it was an
interesting fighting draw.} 25. Rb3 (25. Ra5 $2 Rc8 $1 $17) 25... Rfe8 26. e5
Rc8 27. Qd7 Rcd8 28. Qc7 Rc8 29. Qd7 Rcd8 30. Qc7 Rc8) 12. Qd2 (12. Bf2 c5 13.
d5 (13. Kh1 Be7 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bxc5 Qxc5 $15) 13... Rd8 $132) (12. Kh1 c5
13. dxc5 Bxc5 $15) 12... c5 13. Rad1 Be7 $132) (10. O-O $1 Na5 $3 11. Bd3 c5
12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 14. Kh1 O-O 15. a3 Nc6 $15) (10. Bb3 {We are
again on our own. The correct move seems to be} Na5 $3 {There is no d5 for the
moment.} 11. Qd2 Bb4 {and if} 12. d5 {then} Bc5 {and we are fine.}) 10... Na5
$3 {This is the best move here.} 11. Bd3 (11. Bb3 Bb4 $1 (11... Be7 12. d5 Qa6)
12. O-O O-O 13. Bf2 Rfd8 $15) 11... Qxb2 {You take on b2 if you want to play
the perfect moves, you memorize this, and you are much better. For example,}
12. O-O ({Or} 12. Rb1 $2 Qa3 13. O-O Bb4 $17 {and Black is better by force.}
14. Qe1 {[%cal Ge3c1] threatening to win our queen but we have}) 12... Qa3 13.
Rab1 $2 (13. Qe1 b6 $132 (13... O-O-O $132)) 13... Bb4 14. Qe1 {[%cal Ge3c1]
Threatening to win our queen but we have} Nd5 15. Bd2 O-O-O 16. Nxd5 Bxd2 17.
Qxd2 exd5 18. Qg5 g6 19. Qxd5 Be6 {Black is better. Will you remember all
this? Most likely not. But you need to go through the lines again.} 20. Qb5
Rhe8 $15 (20... Rd5 $15) 1/2-1/2

