{[%evp 0,33,19,38,42,37,76,65,68,58,58,41,49,49,52,-2,-2,-5,35,22,36,32,32,33,
24,8,22,26,20,32,32,37,38,34,48,48] this is the game Mastrovasilis
D-Simeonidis 2008} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 {
This is probably the most important position in the Scandinavian Defense! You
should be very careful with the move order. There are 3 main plans for White: 
1) 6.Ne5, followed by 7.Bc4 or 7.Bf4!   2) 6.Bd2 followed by 7.Ne5!(which s a
hazardous and unknown little system!) or 6.Bd2 followed by 7.Bc4 which by
transposition is taking us to the mainline of the NEO-SCANDINAVIAN  3) RANDOM
MOVES BY WHITE ...like 6.Bd3-Nc6!!(see 2 games by GM Cornette), 6.Be2 followed
by b4-b5 ideas or 6.Be2 followed by simple development, etc. A very important
thing to remember is that at any time White can stop to follow the main theory
and just develop the pieces with no particular ambitions. Our best bet in the
Scandinavian is to wait for random developing moves.} 6. Bd2 {Let us a check
the line which I consider to be the best line in the whole Scandinavian. We
are lucky that Bc4 is the mainline which is not really a dangerous position.} (
6. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5c4] Now he threatens Nc4. I need to make some room for the
queen.} c6 $1 {only move} 7. Bc4 $1 {a famous and popular line...however, 7.
Bf4! is better!} (7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Nc4 Qd8 $5 (8... Qc7) 9. Bf4 Nb6 10. Ne3 Bg6
11. d5 $2 Nfxd5 12. Nexd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Qxd5 cxd5 15. Bb5+ Kd8 16.
O-O-O e6 17. c4 a6 18. Ba4 Rc8 $19) ({Some grandmaster played} 7. Bd3 $5 {
against me.} Bxd3 8. Qxd3 {I played 8...Qa6 which was not so good and I should
have played} Nbd7 $1 {with an about equal game more or less.} 9. Nc4 (9. Nxd7
Nxd7 10. O-O Nf6 $1 11. Bf4 e6 12. Be5 Be7 $5 $132 (12... Nd7 13. Rad1 O-O-O
$13) 13. Qg3 O-O 14. Ne4 Ne8 (14... Kh8) 15. Rfe1 Qd5 $132) 9... Qc7 $1 10. Qf3
(10. Bg5 e6 11. O-O Be7 12. Rfe1 O-O 13. Rad1 b5 $1 14. Ne5 Rad8 $15) 10... Nb6
11. Bf4 Qd8 $1 (11... Qd7 12. Ne5 Qxd4 13. Rd1 Qc5 14. O-O e6 15. a3 a5 16.
Rfe1 Be7 17. Ne4 (17. Nxf7 Kxf7 18. Be3 Qf5 19. Qxf5 exf5 20. Bxb6 Bd8 21. Na4
Re8 $11) 17... Nxe4 18. Qxe4 O-O 19. Nd7 Nxd7 20. Rxd7 Rfd8 21. Rxb7 Bf6 $11)
12. Ne5 e6 13. O-O (13. O-O-O Bb4 14. Kb1 O-O 15. Bg5 $6 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 Nfd5 $15
) 13... Be7 14. Rad1 O-O $11 (14... Nbd5 $1 15. Nxd5 cxd5) 15. Bg3 Nc8 $3 16.
Rfe1 (16. Nc4 Nd6 17. Nxd6 Bxd6 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Ne4 Nxe4 20. Qxe4 Qd5 $1 21.
Qxd5 cxd5 $15) (16. Na4 Nd6 17. Nc5 Rc8 18. b3 (18. Rfe1 Nf5 19. Nxb7 Qb6 20.
Nc5 Qxb2) (18. c3 Nf5 19. Nxb7 Qb6 20. Nc5 Qxb2) 18... Nf5) 16... Nd6 17. Qd3
Nf5) (7. Bf4 $1 {a dangerous and unknown system! . ...do not forget to play 7..
.Nbd7!} Nbd7 $1 {You don't even need to know many moves here.} (7... e6 $2 8.
g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 $6 (9. h4 {and White is much better.} Bb4 10. Rh3 $1 $36 (10. Bd2
Qb6 {gavrilakis-papaioannou 0-1 2008})) 9... Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 $15) 8. Nc4 $1
{This is the correct move.} (8. Qd2 Nxe5 $5 (8... e6 $13) 9. dxe5 Rd8 $13 10.
Bd3 Nh5 11. O-O g6 12. Bg5 Bg7 13. h3 Bxe5 14. Rfe1 f6 $15) (8. g4 Be6 $1 {
SOS ...AS MENTIONED BEFORE, when White goes g4, i ALWAYS play Be6! ...if it is
a ...legal move!!} 9. Nxd7 (9. Nc4 Bxc4 10. Bxc4 e6 $13 {Somebody may say,
"But just a second, Ioannis, you said yourself that with the pair of bishops
in this structure and queens on the board, White is slightly better." Well,
but there is a huge concession here: The move g4. This changes things. We have
a solid position and if White fails to do something with this g4 move, he will
immediately end up worse, of course. So, in fact, this is a perfect position
