{This is an example of a very quiet play by White which is, as always,
unsuccessful in the Scandinavian. At this moment, we are not seeing concrete
theory but concepts which is far more critical. White can play unambitious and
quiet setups in numerous different ways. All the time, we get a fine game by
nice developing moves.} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 c6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6.
Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 e6 {This is good enough. It is the old mainline but we won't be
playing this.} 8. Ne5 Nbd7 {All of a sudden, White starts to make second-rate
moves.} 9. Nxd7 Nxd7 10. O-O {All the time in these situations, Black gets a
good game, for example, I played} Qb6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gd7f6] At any moment, if
White plays passively, we are ready to reach such a setup and move the queen
again and play Bd6, Nf6 and get a great game.} ({We should not be obsessed
with the} 10... Bb4 {concept. We have already mentioned that this Bb4 concept
and taking on c3 does not work at all when the White pawn is on d3 because the
White bishop would generally be very active on the diagonal then.}) ({Another
possibility would have been} 10... Qc7 {This is also good. For example,} 11.
Re1 {I can castle long.} O-O-O {Yes, Black has every right to play like this.}
({Or I can play a move like} 11... Nf6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8,Ge8c8] It is a very
active move and already we want to play Bd6, castle short or long, depending
on our mood and Black is doing great.})) {My the opponent did not dare to
sacrifice a pawn and played} 11. Bc1 ({After} 11. Be3 {I was probably going to
take this pawn} Qxb2 {because I don't really see a big threat. Black is solid
enough to keep his extra pawn without big consequences.}) 11... Nf6 {Already
Black is better. It is very important to note once again that against passive
setups by White, we have every right to play Qa5 and then lose a tempo with
Qb6 or Qc7, consolidate and get a great game.} 12. Bb3 {We have already
discussed that a bishop standing on b3 quite often is out of play.} Bd6 13. Ne2
{I really like my move now:} Qc7 {[%cal Gc7h2] Taking control of all the
squares along this very important diagonal.} 14. h3 {And already Black is
slightly better. Of course, the Bb3 is passive, Black has very active pieces
and now Black is to choose whether to castle short or long. I believe he has
every right to play more ambitiously and that is why I castled long.} O-O-O {
[%cal Gc6c5,Gh7h6,Gg7g5] Intending to break with c5. Another idea is, of
course, to break with h6 and g5. Black was better and in the end, I won.} 15.
c3 c5 16. Bc2 Bxc2 17. Qxc2 cxd4 18. Qa4 d3 19. Nd4 a6 20. Rd1 e5 21. Nf5 g6
22. Bg5 gxf5 23. Bxf6 e4 24. Bxh8 Rxh8 25. b4 Qe7 26. b5 Qe5 27. Qc4+ Kb8 28.
g3 Rg8 29. Qxf7 Rxg3+ 0-1

