{Now we are in the session with the b2-b4 move and we want to see typical
ideas against it.} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Be2 {When
the opponent is out of the book with quiet moves. Usually we don't want to
play Nc6 as this is unnecessary complications. We want to play c6, take the
bishop out, e6, and stabilize as we have already mentioned.} c6 6. O-O {
We are already out of book. You will get such positions very often in the
Scandinavian against opponents who don't like to follow mainline theory.} Bg4 (
6... Bf5 {could have been played as well.}) ({I could have played} 6... g6 {
[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] but I would say that this is way too modern for me.}) 7. b4
{This move now is, in fact, quite interesting because now b7 is under attack ,
but there was no other solution because I have to take out my bishop. We need
to know in all the setups with b4: When b4 is not a gambit, we retreat and
don't take it. We don't want his rook to appear on b7.} Qc7 (7... Qxb4 {
This doesn't seem to be a good move at all.} 8. Rb1 {[%cal Gb1b7] White will
capture on b7.}) {Look now, he goes} 8. b5 {What do we do? We ignore this pawn
and we are ready when he takes on c6 to take even with the pawn if necessary!
This is the most important thing.} e6 {I simply develop my pieces.} 9. Rb1 (9.
bxc6 Nxc6 {possibly I would take with the knight here.} (9... bxc6)) 9... Be7 {
I could have even put it on d6.} 10. h3 Bh5 11. d4 O-O {This is a bit
inaccurate.} ({Here I should have played} 11... Nbd7 $1 {and when he takes} 12.
bxc6 {quite often, I take with the pawn.} bxc6 $132 {This is a crucial thing
to note. bxc6 is counterintuitive because we are used to this pawn being a
weakness. But this pawn is standing in a closed file. Without the White
c2-pawn, the c6 pawn would be weak because rooks could attack it. Now, c6 is
very safe, controlling essential squares. Now I just need to castle and, at
some moment, I may even push c5 taking over the initiative.}) 12. Ne5 Bxe2 13.
Qxe2 Nbd7 14. bxc6 bxc6 15. Bf4 Bd6 16. Nxd7 Nxd7 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. Ne4 {
Now I was very slightly worse because he played very precisely.} Qc7 19. Qa6
Rab8 20. Rb3 e5 21. dxe5 Nxe5 {But I managed with a pawn sacrifice to
neutralize his initiative and draw.} 22. Rc3 h6 23. f4 Rb6 24. Qa4 Nd7 25. Qd4
c5 26. Nxc5 Nxc5 27. Rxc5 Rc6 28. Rxc6 Qxc6 29. f5 Qxc2 30. Qxa7 f6 31. a4 Rd8
32. a5 Rd2 33. Qa8+ Kh7 34. a6 Qc5+ 35. Kh1 Ra2 36. Qb7 Qc4 37. Rf3 1/2-1/2

