1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Be2 c6 6. O-O Bf5 7. b4 Qd8 8.
Rb1 e6 ({The move} 8... h6 $5 {should be taken into account very seriously.
This is very important. Should I keep my bishop or allow Nh4, Bg6, Nxg6? The
problem of h6 is that we are losing too much time so we need to consider
playing it or avoiding it every time separately; it won't be a matter of
theory.}) (8... a6 {I don't believe this is a good move, in fact, because this
a4 and b5 gains in strength.} 9. a4 e6 10. b5 axb5 11. axb5 {The opening of
the a-file I consider it to be irrelevant here.} Bd6 12. bxc6 bxc6 {Although
this is still playable, I would rather keep both a-pawns on the board, and I
feel that Black rather wins White's a2-pawn rather than losing his a7-pawn. If
we want to play for a win, we may want to keep some extra pawns on the board.})
9. b5 Bd6 10. d4 O-O 11. h3 ({If he takes on c6} 11. bxc6 {I take with my
b-pawn.} bxc6) 11... Nbd7 12. Bd3 Bxd3 {We exchange everything.} 13. Qxd3 Qc7 {
From now on, if he takes on c6, most likely I will take with my queen.} 14. Rd1
(14. bxc6 Qxc6 $15 {and Black is better because of the pressure along the
c-line.} (14... bxc6 $5)) 14... Rac8 {I wouldn't say it is equal but slightly
better for Black.} 15. bxc6 bxc6 {I took with the b-pawn due to calculation.}
16. Qa6 ({If he goes} 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 {once again, he has a damaged pawn
structure.} Nf6 18. Qd3 c5 {and he will end up with a weak pawn somewhere.})
16... Rb8 17. Ba3 Bxa3 18. Qxa3 h6 19. Rb3 Nb6 20. Ne5 Rfd8 21. Na4 Ne4 22. Nc5
Nxc5 23. Qxc5 Rbc8 24. c4 f6 25. Nf3 e5 26. Rbb1 e4 27. Nd2 Re8 28. Qf5 e3 29.
fxe3 Rxe3 30. Re1 Qe7 31. Qf2 Rxe1+ 32. Rxe1 Qb4 33. c5 Nd5 0-1

