{[%evp 0,24,28,17,53,35,65,68,74,59,54,60,47,3,27,27,14,-6,8,8,-8,-13,-9,-39,
-3,-32,-107] Sethuraman is an outstanding grandmaster from India. We used to
play for the same team.} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. Be2 Nc6 5. Nc3 $6
{We need to note that this move is, in fact, not very good because now the
square d4 is permanently weakened.} Qd7 {Now at any moment, my knight can jump
to d4 after I take his knight on f3. Here, in fact, we are doing really great.}
6. b4 {[%cal Rb5c6,Rf3c6,Gg4f3,Gb4b5,Ye2f3,Yc6d4] which is totally wrong, I
would say. When he plays b5, I intend to take on f3, if bxc6 Bxc6 back. And if
he takes on f3 back, jump to d4 and Black is better.} ({If he goes} 6. h3 {
most likely, I am going to take} Bxf3 $1 7. Bxf3 O-O-O {[%cal Gc6d4] There are
no such moves as Bg4 and there will never be, and we are ready, at the right
moment, to jump to d4.}) (6. O-O O-O-O 7. d3 (7. h3 {I will consider taking and
} Bf5) 7... e5 {It's the same idea.} 8. h3 (8. Be3) 8... Bxf3 ({Even} 8... Bf5
{is very strong because his move Nh4 can hardly ever be annoying because then
I go Be6 and, of course, attack with f6 and g5. Already here, Black has a
considerable advantage.}) ({If I put it} 8... Be6 9. Ng5 {This move can be
annoying at a good moment.}) (8... Bf5 9. Be3 f6 {and g5 speeds up our attack.}
) (8... Bf5)) 6... O-O-O 7. O-O (7. b5 {We all know, it is written in every
book, that flank activity like this with b4 and b5 is best met with play in
the center if this is possible.} Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nd4 9. O-O {Here play in the
center is quite possible and that is far more important than these b5 and a4
moves.} e5 {Here the next move is probably going to be f5 or maybe Nf6
directly with very active piece play. If you have active piece play, you are
really not worried about flank attacks.}) 7... e5 {Black is already better.} 8.
Rb1 f5 {In fact, if you ask the computer, it will tell you that Black is
already better.} 9. d3 Nf6 $1 {Anyway, I played a perfect move here as well.
Again, Black is better, there is no doubt about that because we have very
active piece play.} ({According to the computer, Black is already better after
} 9... e4 10. dxe4 Bxb4 $15 {which I failed to see.}) ({I cannot take on b4 yet
} 9... Bxb4 {because} 10. Nxe5 {and he has a good game.}) 10. Be3 e4 ({The
computer says that} 10... Qe8 {is giving Black, in fact, a big advantage.}) 11.
dxe4 {and now} Qxd1 (11... Bxb4 12. Qxd7+ Rxd7 13. Bb5 $11) (11... Qe8 {
[%cal Gf8b4] which I totally failed to see gives Black a very big advantage.
After every continuation I can take on b4.} 12. Nd4 ({After} 12. Qc1 {maybe
even take} fxe4 {and Black is, in fact, much better.}) 12... Bxb4 $17) 12.
Rfxd1 Rxd1+ (12... Bxb4 $1 {Is the better move order} 13. Nd5 fxe4 14. Nxb4
Nxb4 $17 15. Rxb4 exf3 16. gxf3 Bf5 17. c3 {Black is much better}) 13. Bxd1
Bxb4 14. Nd5 fxe4 (14... Rd8) 15. Nxf6 $1 gxf6 16. Nd4 Bxd1 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18.
Rxb4 Rd8 (18... Bxc2 19. Bxa7 Kd7 20. Rd4+ Ke6 21. Rc4) 19. Rxe4 Bxc2 20. Rd4
a6 1/2-1/2

