1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c4] He
is threatening Nc4.} c6 7. Bf4 {In fact, this is a better move and a very
dangerous system.} e6 {is already a mistake and White is better!} ({The
correct move is} 7... Nbd7 8. Nc4 Qd8 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gc4d6]} e6 10. Nd6+ (10.
O-O-O {and here we start calculating and most likely} Nb6 {is the right move
with fine counterplay.} 11. Ne5 {Here, I will consider this very annoying move:
} Bb4 {and the game, in practical terms, is very unclear.}) 10... Bxd6 11. Bxd6
Qa5 {[%cal Ge8c8]}) 8. g4 {I would have played Be6 if that was a legal move
because Be6 is always good after g4.} Bg6 9. h4 Bb4 10. Bd2 {This resembles
typical ideas but White is better here as analysis shows. But during the game
you don't know this.} Qb6 {We were out of book.} 11. h5 Be4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13.
c3 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 Bd6 {Now, all of a sudden, I think I am fine.} 15. O-O-O {
Nd7 is an unnecessary risk and I played the solid move.} Qc7 {Maybe White is
very slightly better.} 16. Kb1 {I think this is a waste of time.} Bxe5 {
Now I took here.} 17. dxe5 {Sometimes these lines with a pawn on e5 are really
good for Black.} Nd7 {A knight against a light-squared bishop tends to be
suitable for Black.} 18. f4 O-O-O {[%cal Gd7e5] In the worst case for us,
White is very slightly better but we are threatening to take on e5.} 19. Qe2 (
19. Qd6 {most likely I would have played} Nb6 20. Qxc7+ Kxc7 {Our knight can
be very tricky in such positions.} 21. Be2 Nd5 22. Rhf1 Ne3 ({Or maybe play} 
22... g6)) 19... Nb6 {Black now has an excellent game, at least equal.} 20. Bg2
Qe7 {[%cal Ge7c5] Our queen works very well together with the knight. So, in
practical terms, Black already is slightly better. Now White played a very,
very strange blunder and he lost immediately.} 21. c4 $4 (21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22.
Rd1 Rxd1+ 23. Qxd1 {and start calculating either} Qh4 {to invade.} ({Or} 23...
Qc5 {this move to invade with Nc4 and everything, this is not an equal game.
It would be a big mistake to say that the bishop is better because we have
pawns on both flanks. This would be a total lack of knowledge. In fact, the
most important principle here is that queen and knight work together much
better than queen and bishop.} 24. Qe2 Nc4 {Here we can create various
problems. For example, I am already threatening} 25. b3 Qg1+ 26. Bf1 Qxf1+))
21... Qb4 22. b3 Na4 {and my opponent trusted me very much and resigned
immediately. This is a lost position all of a sudden.} 0-1

